{[%evp 0,8,31,39,26,-11,54,35,32,33,37] Modern (or evergreen) ideas in the
Makogonov attack.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Nf3 {
[#]The systems based on an early h2-h3 wear the name of the Soviet
International Master Vladimir Makogonov who has used it with success more than
half a century ago. Spassky revealed the essence of this opening very clearly:
"White prepares the bishop's development to e3 by defending against the threat
of ...Ng4. Besides, he has g2-g4 in mind, when unlike in the Saemisch attack,
the f3-square is available for the knight". I would add that the bishop could
land on e3 after the intermediate Bc1-g5, ...h7-h6, too. As usual in the
King's Indian, Black has several ways and move orders of reacting in the
center, but the most important structure arises after} e5 (6... Na6 7. Be3 e5
8. d5 {is another possible move order.}) 7. d5 {[#]For a long time, White's
most popular choice was Bc1-g5, pinning the f6-knight and thus aiming to cause
Black to worsen his coordination on the way to prepare ...f7-f5. But during
the past years, players with White have discovered that leaving the path free
for the g-pawn offers very consistent kingside play, and this is how after,
say,} a5 {(or 7...Na6)} 8. Be3 {has become very fashionable. I cannot help
thinking that fashion really is a torturous thing. Years ago I heard many
players naming the systems with h2-h3 and Bc1-g5 "The Makogonov Attack". But
the truth is that in all recorded games with "his" system, Vladimir Andreevich
used the move order 5.h3 0-0 6.Be3, meaning that fashion has more or less
returned to the beginnings. In this article we will examine three typical
scenarios: 1) Black ignores the kingside and prepares his attack on the
opposite wing, leaving White free hands with the plan based on g2-g4.2) Black
opens the kingside before White plays g2-g4 3) Black combines the two ideas.
The first situation, illustrated in the next example, usually leads to slow
maneuvering, when superior strategic understanding may result in apparently
"easy" wins for either side.} *

