{[%evp 0,61,25,29,30,-4,33,35,35,35,39,34,34,34,25,18,22,-9,48,55,70,69,79,26,
36,38,17,24,62,55,55,50,84,51,99,73,73,21,12,20,82,82,82,44,104,111,183,147,
207,259,262,447,436,435,435,465,455,465,505,506,506,514,587,432]} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 O-O 5. Nf3 d6 6. h3 e5 7. d5 a5 8. g4 c6 ({A slightly
unusual move order. Black usually starts his queenside plan with} 8... Na6 9.
Be3 Nc5 10. Nd2 a4 {eventually transposing to the text later.}) 9. Be3 a4 {[#]}
10. a3 $5 {The first interesting strategic moment. White deprives himself of
the standard pawn attack based on b2-b3, thus making it clear that he intends
to attack on the kingside mainly. The idea behind the last move is to exclude
the possibility of ...a4-a3, when Black could get some play on the dark
squares.} ({If} 10. Nd2 {White has to count with} a3 ({True, Black could also
prepare this with} 10... Qa5 {[%cal Ga4a3] For White it would be not simple to
keep his structure intact as after, say,} 11. Rb1 {preparing to meet ...a4-a3
with b2-b4, Black has} Na6 {renewing the threat.}) 11. b4 ({If} 11. b3 Na6 12.
Be2 Nb4 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gc6d5] followed by ...Bd7 and ...cxd5 White may have to
use some of his forces to maintain the stability along the c-file, thus
reducing the impact of his attack on the kingside.}) 11... Na6 12. Rb1 c5 {
[%cal Ga6b4,Ga6c5] Ensuring the knight either the b4- or the c5-square.} 13.
bxc5 Nxc5 {True, the queenside situation is not one-sided, as Black also has
weaknesses along the b-file, but once again the new structure would most
likely distract White's attention from his main plan.}) 10... Qa5 {[%cal Gf6e4]
} 11. Nd2 {This knight retreat makes part of White's general harmonious
regrouping. The knight defends both e4 and b3 and is ready to jump to c4 after
an exchange on d5. Besides, it clears the d1-h5 diagonal, allowing him to
over-defend the g4-pawn and prepare h4-h5.} Nbd7 12. Be2 {[%cal Ge2h5,Ge3h6,
Ge3a7,Ge2a6] [#]I would like to highlight the minor pieces' placement. This
would be a dream regrouping in the classical system (5.Nf3 and 6.Be2), but in
those lines, the dark-squared bishop usually does not have the time to develop
before Nf3-d2. Both bishops are optimally placed, as they control important
diagonals on both wings. At the moment, the pressure against the queenside may
seem abstract, but Black cannot do without ...cxd5, cxd5 and then the bishops
will help to restrict Black's plans, at least partly.} Nc5 {[%cal Gc5e4,Gf6e4]}
13. Kf1 $1 {Another typical move and the best way to defend e4.} (13. f3 {
would make g4-g5 ineffective (either before or after h4-h5) as the enemy
knight could jump to h5, defending the h-file and controlling the weak square
on f4. The attack based on h4-h5 only is less effective than, say, in the
Saemisch attack, as the queen, does not have the d2-square at her disposal,
thus depriving White of the typical Bh6.}) (13. Qc2 {is not without drawbacks
either. Firstly, the queen could get under some pressure after the opening of
the c-file. But not less important is the fact that at the time being the
queen is optimally placed on its initial square, for the familiar reason that
it keeps both wings under control. In the short term, her Majesty over-defends
g4, allowing h3-h4-h5.}) 13... cxd5 14. cxd5 Bd7 {We should also say a few
words about Black's minor pieces. Apparently, all of them stand on good
squares, but a deeper look reveals that, as so many times in the blocked
King's Indian structures, there is some concurrence for the d7-square. This
will soon be very relevant, as g4-g5 makes part of White's main plan.} 15. h4
b5 {[#]The mutual pawn storms have started at the same moment. But deciding
about the best way to continue is essential now.} 16. h5 $1 ({Apparently there
is no difference between this and} 16. g5 {intending to meet 16...Ne8 with 17.
h5, but Black has} Nh5 $1 17. Bxh5 gxh5 {The point is that in the absence of
the light-squared bishop tends to leave White over-extended, with many
weaknesses behind the far advanced pawns. If} 18. Qxh5 b4 19. axb4 Qxb4 {
White's attack is nowhere, while Black already has queenside threats.}) {[#]}
16... Rfb8 {Optically, the most harmonious move. Black has managed to evacuate
the rook just in time before being forced to retreat with his knight to the
back rank. At the same time, he reinforces the threat ...b5-b4.} (16... b4 $5 {
is an interesting, but not entirely sound try to speed up the attack.} 17. Nc4
{As mentioned above, White's minor pieces are ready to react on the queenside.}
Qc7 18. axb4 Ncxe4 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 {Abstractly speaking, the exchange of a wing
pawn for a central one favors Black, but before evaluating the position we
should play over a few more moves:} 20. Nb6 {The knight uses the bishop's help
to exchange the d7-bishop. Since the bishops and the b4-pawn control all
squares along the a-file, Black has to abandon the a-pawn.} Rab8 21. Rc1 Qd8
22. Nxd7 Qxd7 23. b5 {This pawn, sustained by both bishops, is likely to
become stronger and stronger after any major piece exchange. Black has lost
the queenside battle but seems to have some chances on the opposite wing.
However, the plan based on ...f7-f5 may backfire, as after exchanges on g6 and
f5 his king would start to feel more uncomfortable than White's.} f5 {[#]} 24.
Qxa4 $1 {Not only grabbing a pawn but also taking measures against ...f5-f4.} (
{The careless} 24. hxg6 $2 {, hoping for a double pawn exchange, ran into} f4 {
with dangerous counterplay in Kozionov, K (2461)-Amonatov, F (2615) St
Petersburg 2018 (0-1, 47)}) 24... Ra8 ({If} 24... f4 25. Qxe4 fxe3 26. Qxe3 $16
{[%csl Rg6,Rg8] White wins a second pawn and stabilizes the kingside. Besides,
the black king faces some discomfort as the g6-pawn is vulnerable (after, for
instance, hxg6 and Bd3).}) 25. Qb4 Qf7 26. Ke1 $5 {This unexpected yet elegant
move is probably strongest. The king readjusts its plans according to the new
circumstances.} ({There is nothing really wrong with} 26. b6 f4 27. Qxe4 fxe3
28. Qxe3 Ra4 {But Black is a bit more active than in the similar line above.
With the king on e1 White is ready for fxe3, reaching a strategically
overwhelming position as there are no weaknesses on the dark-squares Black
could connect his hopes with.}) 26... Bf6 {[%cal Gf6g5] Hoping for ...Bg5.} 27.
hxg6 Qxg6 (27... hxg6 $2 28. gxf5 gxf5 29. Rg1+ Kh8 30. Bd3 {offers White a
decisive attack. After Bxe4 it will not take long to insert either the queen
or the queen's rook into the attack, the former along the fourth rank and the
latter along the first rank, after, say, Kd2.}) 28. Bd3 {[%cal Rd3g6] The pin
along the light diagonal is very molesting. If} Qxg4 29. Bxe4 Qxe4 30. Qxe4
fxe4 31. b6 $18 {the material is equal, but the white bishop is by far
superior to the black one and the b-file will soon decide.}) 17. g5 Ne8 {
The knight has been forced onto a passive square and it will take some time
before it joins the queenside battle.} (17... Nxh5 $2 {is simply bad now, as
after} 18. Bxh5 gxh5 19. Qxh5 {White can use the h-file for a decisive attack.}
) {[#]Now is the moment to talk about White's kingside plan in detail. His
attack has a double character. It surely is an attack against the king, but if
this would be all Black may have resources to resist. But at the same time,
this is a strategic attack! White has, for instance, the possibility of
exchanging the light-squared bishops with Bg4 or make use of the chronic
weaknesses on f6 and h6. He sometimes achieves the latter by transferring his
knight from d2 to g4 (Kg2, Nf1-h2-g4). These combined aspects make Black's
situation critical already.} 18. hxg6 hxg6 (18... fxg6 {would not spare Black
problems:} 19. Na2 Nc7 20. Bg4 $16 {This not only offers the bishops' exchange,
after which the c6-square would be chronically weak but also clears the
queen's path to the h-file. The latter is even more relevant if Black tries to
avoid the former:} Be8 $2 21. Qf3 N7a6 22. Nb4 Nxb4 $2 23. Bxc5 dxc5 24. Be6+
Kh8 25. Rxh7+ $1 {mating soon.}) {[#]} 19. Na2 $1 {Suddenly, Black needs some
more time to prepare his queenside break. Now is when the move a2-a3 proves
very useful.} Nc7 20. Kg2 N7a6 21. Rh4 $1 {[%cal Gd1h1,Yh4h7,Yh7g7,Rh1h6]
Threatening Qh1, Rh7, Rxg7+, Qh6+ and Rh1, mating.} f5 {Desperation.} ({
The aforementioned plan is so effective that after, say,} 21... Nb3 22. Nxb3
axb3 {White does not even have to care about moving his knight:} 23. Qh1 bxa2
24. Rh7 $18) 22. gxf6 Bxf6 23. Qh1 $1 (23. Rh6 {is also good enough for a win,
but why to waste a whole tempo?}) 23... Qd8 ({If} 23... Bxh4 24. Qxh4 Qd8 25.
Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6,Ga1h1] followed by Bf6 and/or Rh1 wins.}) 24. Rh7 {The rest
is simple.} Rb7 25. Qh2 Be8 26. Rh1 Rg7 27. Rxg7+ Bxg7 28. Qh7+ Kf8 29. Bh6
Bxh6 30. Qxh6+ Ke7 31. Bg4 1-0

