{[%evp 0,80,27,27,30,-16,32,44,44,35,35,35,35,28,41,17,47,27,48,45,45,52,71,14,
6,12,3,-1,3,0,31,25,13,-19,-19,-19,-11,0,2,2,-19,-4,-5,-25,54,54,54,54,54,49,
64,64,75,66,128,70,78,0,26,-64,-60,-102,-102,-155,-155,-155,-155,-155,-171,
-209,-194,-216,-237,-235,-235,-235,-213,-182,-196,-1996,-1975,-983,-983]
Things are completely different if Black plays an early ...f7-f5.} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5 Nh5 8. g3 f5 9. exf5 gxf5 {
[#]Optically, Black's position seems very appealing. He has a mobile centre
while White has invested two pawn moves into what seems like a general
kingside weakening. But this is by far not such an one-sided issue. First of
all, Black has also neglected his development and cannot sustain his kingside
initiative at this stage. The g3-pawn is useful for preventing the resulute ...
e5-e4 followed by ...f5-f4, while the h-pawn will sooner or later sustain the
break g3-g4, not only fighting for the e4-square but also opening files for
the attack.} 10. Ng5 Qe8 11. Be2 Nf6 12. Be3 Na6 {Black has to catch up in
development and keep his central pawns on their actual positions for the time
being. While ...f5-f4 is not easy to carry out, ...e5-e4 would clear the d4-
and f4-squares for White's minor pieces. In fact, at a later stage, it will be
White who will try to force one of the pawns to advance.} 13. Qd2 Bd7 14. O-O-O
{[#]} h6 ({Black has to weaken his kingside in order to push the knight back
before it is too late. If} 14... Nc5 15. g4 $1 h6 ({The neutral} 15... Kh8 {
led to a strategic catastrophe on the light squares after} 16. gxf5 Bxf5 17.
Bxc5 dxc5 18. Bg4 Bg6 19. Ne6 Rf7 20. Rde1 $16 {Rodshtein,M (2678)-Socko,B 
(2587) Stockholm 2015 (1-0, 49) Miau}) 16. Ne6 $1 Bxe6 17. dxe6 Qxe6 {White is
perfectly coordinated, his e2-bishop has no rival on the light squares and
Black's king is vulnerable. From the possible continuations, I would choose}
18. Rhg1 {[%cal Gg4f5,Ge3h6] keeping Bxh6 and gxf5 in reserve. If} Kh7 19. Qc2
e4 20. Nb5 $16 {[%cal Gb5d4] followed by Nd4 with strong initiative.}) 15. Nf3
Nc5 16. Nh4 $5 {[%csl Rf5] The most principled way of using the knight which
has just been helped to return into play. Black will soon have problems
defending f5.} (16. g4 {is also playable, but Black could mud up the waters
with} Nfe4 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Qc2 Nxf2 $5 19. Bxf2 fxg4 20. hxg4 e4) {[#]} 16...
Nce4 {Black decides to get some breathing space by exchanging the relatively
unstable c5-knight and regroup with its colleague.} ({Once again, the neutral} 
16... Kh7 $2 {leads to trouble after} 17. g4 Nfe4 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Qc2 $16 {
Goganov,A (2635)-Bejtovic,J (2370) Sweden 2017 (1-0, 39)}) 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18.
Qc2 Ng5 19. Bd3 $1 {Forcing the central pawn to advance.} e4 20. Be2 Rc8 21.
Kb1 {[%cal Gh4g2,Gg2f4] [#]White has stabilized the position to his favor and
is ready to increase the pressure with Ng2-f4.} c5 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black's only
chance for counterplay.} 22. dxc6 $1 {Opening the d-file and leaving d4 clear
for the bishop. Against other moves, Black would get strong counterplay with ..
. b7-b5.} Rxc6 23. Qd2 {This was not absolutely necessary.} ({White could have
initiated his regrouping with} 23. Ng2 {since} b5 {is not dangerous due to} 24.
c5 $16 dxc5 $6 25. Bxb5) 23... Be6 24. Bxg5 $2 {A curious decision from a
King's Indian specialist like Radjabov. Due to the bishop's unchallenged
pressure along the long diagonal Black will have enough counterplay.} ({
The more natural} 24. Bd4 $1 {[%cal Gh4g2,Gg2f4] followed by Ng2-f4 would have
retained a stable advantage.} Bxc4 $2 {loses material to} 25. Bxg7 Bxe2 (25...
Kxg7 26. Qd4+ {[%csl Rc4] wins the bishop.}) 26. Bxh6 Bd3+ 27. Ka1 {winning an
exchange and retaining chances for an attack against the weakened king.}) 24...
hxg5 25. Qxg5 Ra6 ({Even stronger would have been} 25... b5 $1 26. cxb5 Ra6 {
with at least enough compensation for the pawns, as} 27. bxa6 $2 Qa4 {wins
quickly. But after the game move, Black also had a promising play and
eventually won.}) 26. Rd2 b5 27. Rc1 Qf7 28. Ng6 Bf6 29. Qh6 Rb8 30. Nf4 Bxc4
31. Rxc4 bxc4 32. Nd5 Bg7 33. Qg5 c3 34. Bc4 cxd2 35. Nf6+ Kf8 36. Nh7+ Ke8 37.
Bxf7+ Kxf7 38. Qxf5+ Kg8 39. Kc2 Rxb2+ 40. Kd1 Rb1+ 0-1

