{[%evp 0,50,27,18,27,-21,32,44,35,35,35,28,28,17,18,27,29,12,22,2,22,-14,19,14,
41,62,58,66,112,112,88,71,97,108,109,110,104,45,69,43,57,34,34,34,47,22,55,57,
66,54,35,-486,-510] We shall now investigate the third situation when Black
makes some queenside developing moves before breaking with ...f7-f5. This
almost always means that White will have played g2-g4 already, making the
fight for the light squares after general exchanges on f5 crucial.} 1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Be3 Nbd7 7. Nf3 e5 8. d5 Nc5 9. Nd2
a5 10. g4 c6 11. Be2 Ne8 {[#]Not a good square for the knight, but we are
familiar with the conflict around the d7-square. In order to carry out ...
f7-f5 Black needs to leave the h3-c8 diagonal open.} 12. Nb3 $5 {An interestig
decision, dictated by the fact that the reserve knight is far from d7.} (12. h4
f5 13. h5 {was also possible, but despite the engines' optimism I wonder
whether White can make any progress after} f4 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. hxg6 hxg6 {
The main thing for Black is to keep the structure as it is as otherwise the
white knights would get the light squares for the blockade.}) 12... Nd7 {
Hoping to return to c5 after ...a5-a4.} ({But} 12... cxd5 13. cxd5 b6 {is
worth considering.}) 13. a4 $5 f5 14. gxf5 gxf5 15. exf5 {[#]} Ndf6 ({Black
cannot activate his back rank knight as after} 15... Nef6 $2 16. dxc6 bxc6 17.
Qxd6 {White simply wins an important pawn.}) ({Or if} 15... Rxf5 16. Qd2 {
[%cal Ge1c1,Gh1g1,Gh3h4,Gh4h5,Ye2g4] followed by 0-0-0, Rhg1, h4-h5, possibly
with Bg4 in between, White has a consistent attack almost for free.}) 16. Bd3
Kh8 17. Rg1 Qe7 18. Nd2 {White obviously hoped to prevent the thematic ...
e5-e4, but as we will see the last move makes it possible under reasonable
circumstances.} ({The developing} 18. Qd2 $5 {planning 0-0-0 followed by the
familiar plan was a safer way to an advantage. If} e4 19. Bc2 {the knight on
b3 suddenly proves useful due to the threat Nd4 and if} c5 20. O-O-O Bxf5 21.
f3 $16 {White keeps the better development, safer king and considerable space
advantage.}) 18... cxd5 19. cxd5 {[%cal Gd2e4] [#]} e4 $1 {Otherwise Nde4
would kill Black strategically.} 20. Ndxe4 Nxe4 21. Nxe4 Bxf5 {The position
has become messy and even if detailed analysis will show that White can make
his extra pawn worth anything, this was not the kind of position he had been
aiming for.} 22. Ng3 ({Objectively,} 22. Nc3 {may be better, but at least
optically} Bd4 23. Kd2 Bxe3+ 24. fxe3 {does not look clear at all.}) 22... Bxd3
23. Qxd3 Qe5 $6 (23... Bxb2 $1 24. Rb1 Be5 $11 {was simpler and better.}) 24.
Ne2 Rf3 25. Rg5 $4 {A terrible blunder.} ({White could stabilize the position
to his favour with} 25. Rg3 Rxg3 26. Nxg3 Qxb2 27. Rb1 {Black has almost no
active pieces left and strategically he is not doing very well either.}) 25...
Qxg5 $1 0-1

