{After having seen a few examples about how the long and heavy strategic
battle flows in these lines, we will examine a few fragments illustrating some
typical elements.[#]King's Indian players love to sacrifice the exchange in
order to turn the g7-bishop into the strongest piece on the board. This is a
typical position where White's numerous weaknesses on the dark squares justify
the next move.} 19... Rf4 $5 20. Qd3 $6 ({White cannot afford} 20. Bxf4 $2 exf4
{In general, such a structure favors Black who can invade the just cleared
dark squares with his pieces, but in this case, the king's presence in the
center makes things worse:} 21. Rc1 Bd4 22. Rg2 a4 $5 $19 {with a decisive
attack on the whole board.}) ({White should have anticipated Black's next
regrouping by over-defending e4, in order to maintain his stability:} 20. Bd3
Nc8 21. Qd2 Nd6 22. Qg2 a4 23. b4 {with chances to maintain the space
advantage.}) 20... Nc8 21. Be2 Nd6 22. Bxc5 (22. Rg4 {does not prevent} Nxe4 $1
{at all, as the a1-rook is hanging.}) 22... b6 23. Bxd6 Qxd6 24. Kd2 Raf8 $15 {
Despite the missing pawn, Black has an excellent play on the dark squares. The
game eventually ended in a draw. In the next example, White treated this issue
more carefully.} 1/2-1/2

