{With his last move (14...f4) Black hoped to get some kingside safety. In fact,
placing another pawn on a dark square is an important strategic concession.[#]
} 15. Bxc5 dxc5 16. Bg4 Nd6 {The structure is similar to that in
Jakovenko-Pavlidis above, but Black does not have the f4-square for his rook.}
17. Bxc8 Qxc8 18. Qf3 a4 19. Qh3 Qe8 {The queen exchange would annihilate
Black's last hope for counterplay.} 20. h5 Rb8 ({Black cannot clear the
f8-square for his bishop as} 20... Rf7 {loses a pawn to} 21. hxg6 hxg6 22. Qh7+
) 21. Rc1 ({I would find it hard to refrain from} 21. h6 {forcing} Bh8 {
when White would play the rest of the game with an extra piece as the bishop
does not count for much.}) 21... c6 22. Rc2 ({White now missed the elegant} 22.
Nxa4 cxd5 23. cxd5 {winning a pawn, since} Qxa4 24. Qe6+ Nf7 25. hxg6 hxg6 26.
Qxg6 $18 {[%cal Gh1h7,Gg6h7] threatening both Qh7 mate and Rh7,}) 0-1

