{Here is one more case of mishandling ...f5-f4 at the highest level.[#]} 14...
f4 $6 ({Much better was} 14... Nxd5 $1 15. exd5 f4 {White cannot keep the
blockade as firm in hand as in the quoted game. Black will get some additional
squares or files. For instance:} 16. Nde4 fxe3 17. fxe3 Nc5 18. Nxc5 dxc5 19.
Ne4 c6 {with entirely adequate black counterplay. The capture on d5 leads to
the exchange of the same pieces under more favorable strategic circumstances
for Black.}) 15. Bxb6 cxb6 16. Qf3 ({The strongest continuation would have been
} 16. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6] Threatening with the familiar h5-h6.} Rf7 17. Qf3 Nc5
18. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Gf1h3] Followed by Bh3 with excellent control on the
light squares and no counterplay for Black. Please note that the exchange on
b6 is favorable only after Black's ...f5-f4, otherwise, the weakness of the
f4-square would more than compensate even for the loss of the a4-pawn.}) 1-0

