{[%evp 0,22,26,27,28,-4,32,39,32,33,33,33,33,21,40,8,21,21,22,-11,22,22,29,2,
-7]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5 {This is
the most important position of the entire system. At this point, it is
important to understand the positional justification of the move 6.h3. Besides
securing the e3-square for the bishop, White is planning to expand on the
kingside by means of g2-g4. The g2-g4 advance, however, is of an ambiguous
nature. I am inclined to consider it as a prophylactic move since Black has
problems to execute his typical plan based on ...f7-f5. In a number of
positions, however, White can start pushing his kingside pawns, thus creating
attacking possibilities on the kingside. This usually happens when Black
starts transferring his minor pieces to the kingside. White's typical
regroupment Be3, Nd2, and Be2 allow him to play on both wings depending on the
concrete circumstances. Of course, White's concept is not without drawbacks.
For instance, the weakness of the f4-square obliges him to keep his pawn on
the d5-square. Otherwise, Black will transfer his knight to e6. Another
important question concerns the position of the white king. Even though the
king should be safe enough in the center, in a long-run, Black has some
unpleasant ...Nd3+ checks. When White is attacking the kingside, the option to
castle queenside looks logical. In some cases, however, White executes the
regroupment Rg1-g3, followed by Kf1-g2. Black's plan is far from being clear.
Usually, he tries to play on both wings. It is important to point out that the
premature f7-f5 leads to troubles since White will have the open g-file and
the weak e4-square at his disposal. Black can also go for active actions on
the queenside but one must remember that White has a strategic advantage in
this sector of the board. Another major drawback in Black's position is the
lack of space - three minor pieces are fighting for the d7-square. In the
current database, I will try to prove that Black does not have a clear
solution to White's setup.} a5 {This seems to be the most natural move in the
position. Black secures the c5-square for his b8-knight. Certainly, this move
would be the choice of someone who has no prior knowledge of this line.
Nevertheless, with his last move, Black gives White time to organize his
forces.} ({The main alternative is} 7... Nh5) ({As explained later} 7... Na6) (
{and} 7... Nbd7 {do not have much of an independent value.}) 8. Be3 {Nowadays,
this is White's most popular move. The old main line used to be 8.Bg5,
creating a pin. It turns out, however, that it is more important to keep the
way of the g-pawn open. Additionally, being on e3, the bishop puts pressure on
Black's queenside.} ({The alternate move order is} 8. g4 Na6 9. Be3 {
transposing below.}) 8... Na6 9. g4 {Black has finished the neutral moves and
needs to choose a concrete setup already. The main continuations are 9...Nd7
and 9...Nc5.} Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gd7c5] Via d7, the knight can be transferred to
either c5 or b6. In this line, very often Black starts playing on the
queenside. Nevertheless, White's long-term prospects on the queenside are
better. That is why Black usually runs out of resources.} (9... c6 {and}) (9...
Bd7 {do not have independent value as Black cannot make progress without ...
Na6-c5 later anyway.}) (9... Nc5 {[%emt 0:00:03] will be examined in line}) 10.
a3 $1 {This is a deep prophylactical move which is designed to prevent 10...
Nc5. White can now answer 10...Nc5 with 11.b4!.} ({If} 10. Rg1 $6 Ndc5 11. h4 (
11. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Ya1a8]} Bd7 {unpins the a6-knight, thus preventing b2-b4.})
11... c6 12. h5 Bd7 13. Nd2 a4 14. a3 cxd5 15. cxd5 b5 {[%cal Gb5b4] with
strong queenside counterplay in Harika,D (2496)-Bologan,V (2608) Caleta 2015 
(0-1, 45).}) 10... Nb6 (10... c6 {This move of Grischuk fails to equalize.} 11.
Rg1 Rb8 {[%cal Gd7c5] Removing the potential pin long the a-file in order to
prepare ...Ndc5.} 12. Nd2 Ndc5 13. Rb1 Ra8 $5 {The way I understand it, this
is a half-waiting move. More details later.} ({The game below actually
included a move repetition with} 13... Nd7 {14.Qf3 Ndc5 15.Qd1 and only then
15...Ra8.} 14. h4 $1 {with White initiative since} ({The idea behind 13...Nd7
probably was to answer} 14. b4 axb4 15. axb4 c5 {[%cal Ga6c5,Ga6b4] , securing
a stable dark square for the a6-knight. White can do better, though.}) 14...
Qxh4 $2 15. g5 f5 16. Rg3 f4 17. Nf3 Qh5 18. Rh3 Qg4 19. Rh4 {[%csl Rg4] wins
the queen.}) ({It is interesting to compare} 13... Kh8 {with the game move:}
14. h4 a4 $5 {[%cal Gd8h4,Gc6d5,Gc8d7,Gb7b5,Gb5b4] Preparing to take on h4
under reasonable circumstances.} 15. Nxa4 {Otherwise Black would speed up his
queenside play with ...cxd5, ...Bd7, ...b5-b4.} Nxa4 16. Qxa4 Qxh4 {[%csl Rh8]
Since there is no knight on d7 as in the previous line, White does not have
the queen trapping plan anymore. But the black king is on an exposed file,
allowing White to gain time for his attack even in the absence of the h-pawn.}
17. Qd1 $1 Bd7 18. Qf3 {[%cal Gf1e2,Gg1h1,Yf3h3] Planning Be2, Rh1, Qh3.} Qf6
19. Qh3 cxd5 20. cxd5 Kg8 {If we compare with the similar line below we can
understand that this loss of time is decisive.} 21. Rh1 h5 22. f3 Rfc8 23. Qh2
hxg4 24. Qh7+ Kf8 25. fxg4 {[%cal Gf1e2,Gh1f1,Ge3h6] Planning Be2 followed by
Rf1 and Bh6.} Bxg4 26. Be2 $5 Bxe2 27. Kxe2 {[%cal Gb1f1] The threat Rf1 is
decisive.} Ke7 28. Qh3 Rh8 29. Qg3 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Ge3g5] White wins the
queen with Bg5 soon.}) 14. Rg3 (14. h4 {is less effective now:} a4 15. Nxa4
Nxa4 16. Qxa4 Qxh4 17. Qd1 Bd7 18. Qf3 Qf6 19. Qh3 cxd5 20. cxd5 Nc5 {This
extra tempo makes a difference. Actually, we talk about two whole tempi, as in
some lines the queen's rook could advance to a4.} 21. Rh1 h5 22. f3 Rfc8 {
The position is by far less clear than the similar line above. The point is
that after} 23. Qh2 $2 hxg4 24. Qh7+ Kf8 25. fxg4 {Black has several ways of
including the knight into the defense/counterattack with ...Nxe4, the most
direct being} Nxe4 26. Nxe4 Qf3 $19) 14... Kh8 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 Nd7 17. Ra1
Rb8 {Another waste of time with the same rook.} ({But if} 17... c5 18. b5 {
[%cal Ga1a8] the knight is pinned so it cannot go to b4 while after} Nc7 19.
Rxa8 Nxa8 20. Be2 $5 {Black is very passive.}) 18. Rxa6 $1 bxa6 19. dxc6 Nb6 {
Tomashevsky,E (2716)-Grischuk,A (2810) Tbilisi 2015 (1-0, 37)} 20. b5 $16) ({
Finally, Black should not display kingside ambitions since after} 10... f5 11.
gxf5 gxf5 12. exf5 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gh1g1] the natural re-capture ...Bxf5 is
impossible, allowing White to build up his kingside initiative with Bd3 and
Rg1. For instance:} Ndc5 13. b4 e4 14. Nd4 Nd3+ {Desperation.} 15. Bxd3 exd3
16. Rg1 Bxf5 17. Nxf5 Rxf5 18. Rxg7+ $1 Kxg7 19. Qg4+ Kf6 20. Ne4+ Ke5 21. Ng3
{1-0 Karpov, A (2619)-Sepp, O (2440) Puhajarve 2013}) (10... Nac5 {will be the
subject of the next line.}) 11. Rg1 {After having reached partial success on
the queenside (the knight's activity on b6 is partly questionable), White
returns to his main plan.} Bd7 12. h4 $1 {It is important to remember that
with the black knight being far away from the f6-square, White is not adviced
to go for Nd2 ideas (the g4-pawn does not need over-protection). When the
d-file is open, Black cannot easily carry out the c7-c6 advance because the
d6-pawn would become a target.} ({This is why I prefer the last move over} 12.
Nd2) 12... Nc5 13. b3 $1 Kh8 14. g5 {[%cal Gf3d2]} a4 {The only way of trying
to give meaning to the knights' placement. It is now or never, as White would
next play Nd2.} (14... f5 15. Nd2 $14) (14... f6 15. Nd2 (15. Be2 fxg5 16. Nxg5
h6 17. Nf3 {Rodshtein,M (2687)-Saric,I (2668) Baku 2016 (1-0, 42)} a4 18. Bxc5
dxc5 19. Rxg6 Rf4 $13) 15... fxg5 (15... Qe7 16. Rb1) 16. hxg5 $14) 15. b4 Nb3
16. Rb1 (16. Ra2 {is also worth considering.}) 16... f5 17. Nd2 (17. h5 gxh5
18. Nh4 Nd4 19. Bd3 $16) 17... Nd4 18. c5 {Putting an end to Black's hopes for
active play. His knight will stand awfully on c8.} Nc8 {[%csl Rc8]} 19. h5 gxh5
20. Qxh5 Nc2+ 21. Kd1 Nxe3+ 22. fxe3 fxe4 23. Rh1 Bf5 24. Bg2 $18 {Schlosser,P
(2516)-Tomazini,Z (2405) Pardubice 2017 (1-0, 41)} *

