{[%evp 0,22,26,27,28,-4,32,39,32,33,33,33,33,21,40,8,21,21,22,-11,22,22,29,2,
-7]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5 a5 8. Be3
Na6 9. g4 Nd7 10. a3 Nac5 {[%cal Ga5a4] The most popular move. After having
provoked the slight queenside weakening a2-a3 Black finally jumps with his
queen's knight to c5, thus creating the threat of blocking the queenside with .
..a5-a4. The knights stand beautifully, defending each other, but the bishop
on c8 might have some objections.} 11. Rg1 ({Since Black's king's knight has
left f6, there is no need of overdefending e4 yet.} 11. Nd2 {allows} Bf6 {
[%cal Gf6g5] planning ...Bg5. In Riazantsev,A (2617)-Inarkiev,E (2675)
Novokuznetsk 2008 (0-1, 48) White did not find anything better than returning
with his knight to f3.}) ({Or if} 11. b4 axb4 12. axb4 Rxa1 13. Qxa1 Nb3 14.
Qd1 Nd4 15. Nxd4 exd4 16. Bxd4 Ne5 {Black has strong initiative for the pawn,
the latest example being} 17. f4 Nf3+ 18. Qxf3 Bxd4 19. Rh2 Qh4+ 20. Kd1 Bxc3
21. Qxc3 Bxg4+ 22. Kc2 {Meskovs,N (2510)-Stabulnieks,K (2133) Riga 2017 (1-0,
57) and now the simplest is} Ra8 $19) 11... a4 12. Nd2 c6 ({The point behind
11.Rg1 is that} 12... Bf6 {[%cal Gf6g5] can be answered with} 13. g5 Be7 {
This is the most logical retreat, as it keeps the pressure on g5, but it does
not solve Black's problems.} (13... Bg7 $6 {is just what it looks to be: a
waste of two tempi.} 14. h4 f5 15. h5 Na6 {[%cal Gf5f4] Aiming at making the
threat ...f5-f4 real.} ({If} 15... f4 16. Bxc5 Nxc5 17. h6 Bh8 18. Qf3 Ra6 19.
O-O-O Bd7 20. Bh3 $16 {[%csl Rh8] Black is doomed to play the rest of the game
with a piece down, as the bishop is immobile on h8.True, White has to
permanently defend g5, but Black's queen is also confined to e7 and d8 in
order to keep White busy. Archangelsky, M (2107)-Jedlicka, A (2325) Teplice
2015 (½-½, 32)}) 16. exf5 Rxf5 (16... gxf5 17. h6 Bh8 18. g6 Bf6 19. Qh5 $18)
17. hxg6 hxg6 {Korchmar,V (2393)-Klimentov,R (2208) Voronezh 2015 (1-0, 52)}
18. Bh3 $5 Ndc5 19. Qc2 {[%cal Ge1c1] Followed by 0-0-0 and the gradual
preparation for the attack along the h-file. Sooner or later the threat Bxf5
will become real, forcing the rook to retreat with a huge strategic advantage
for White.}) 14. h4 f6 15. gxf6 ({Under the given circumstances White cannot
keep the tension:} 15. Qc2 fxg5 16. hxg5 Rf4 17. Bxf4 exf4 18. Nf3 Nb3 19. Rd1
Ndc5 $44) 15... Bxf6 16. h5 g5 17. h6 Kh8 18. Qh5 $16 {By this moment White's
advantage is almost decisive, Potkin, V (2621)-Yuffa, D (2444) Vladivostok
2014 (½-½, 62)}) ({The following rapid game, having a strong player on the
black side, is relevant about White's plan if Black more or less marks time
with neutral moves:} 12... Kh8 13. Qc2 c6 14. O-O-O Nb6 15. Kb1 Bd7 16. Be2 Qe7
17. h4 cxd5 18. cxd5 Rac8 19. h5 g5 20. Rc1 h6 21. Qd1 Bf6 22. Bb5 Qe8 23. Qe2
Bd8 24. Bxd7 Qxd7 25. Qb5 Qe7 26. Ne2 $16 {With complete control on the light
squares, Urkedal,F (2572)-Fressinet,L (2662) chess.com INT (rapid) 2018 (1-0,
65)}) 13. Qc2 Nb6 {Black speeds up his development, but with the knight, in
front of the b-pawn he will have problems creating concrete counterplay.} ({
Even though optically logical,} 13... Qa5 {is not that promising either.} 14.
O-O-O Rb8 {[%cal Gc6d5,Gb7b5] Planning ...cxd5 and if cxd5 then ...b7-b5, but
White can make use of Black's strong commitment to deviate from the natural
course at the right moment.} 15. Be2 $1 $146 {As we will see, it is important
to defend f3 and g4 in advance.} (15. Na2 $6 {justified Black's plan:} cxd5 16.
cxd5 b5 17. Nb4 Bb7 18. Kb1 Rfc8 19. Rc1 Nf6 20. g5 Nh5 21. Be2 Nf4 $11 {
with perfect stability for Black, Tomazini,A (2309)-Golubov,S (2446) Pardubice
2015 (½-½, 35)}) (15. h4 {is a bit premature as after} cxd5 16. exd5 {
Black can try to mud up the waters with} e4 $5 17. Ndxe4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Ne5 19.
Be2 {It is now that it would be useful to have the bishop on e2 in advance.} b5
20. cxb5 Bd7) (15. Rg3 $5 {may be an equally good way of defending f3.}) 15...
cxd5 (15... b5 $2 {simply loses material to} 16. dxc6 b4 17. axb4 $18) 16. exd5
$1 {The familiar deviation from the standard play.} ({If} 16. cxd5 b5 17. Na2 {
play more or less transposes to the game quoted above.}) 16... Re8 (16... e4 {
does not work anymore:} 17. Ndxe4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Ne5 19. f4 $18 {[%cal Ge4d6]
followed by Nxd6.}) 17. Nb5 $5 {Forcing the bishop to occupy a passive square
and forgetting about ...b7-b5.} Bf8 18. h4 $16 {White's attack develops
unhindered while Black's play has come to a dead end.}) (13... b6 $6 {has been
played a few times but is not easy to understand.} 14. O-O-O cxd5 15. cxd5 b5
16. Bxb5 Ba6 17. Bxa6 Rxa6 18. Na2 Qa8 19. Nb4 Rc8 20. Kb1 Nb3 21. Qd3 Ndc5 22.
Bxc5 Nxc5 23. Qe2 $18 {Esipenko,A (2540)-Kotau,A (2189) Mamaia 2017 (1-0, 27)})
({Finally, if} 13... cxd5 14. cxd5 $1 {Black cannot prepare his queenside pawn
attack.} Qa5 (14... b5 15. Bxb5 Ba6 16. Bxa6 Rxa6 {only apparently wins a
tempo over 13...b6 above, as White can take advantage of the fact that he has
not castled with} 17. Kf1 $16 {taking the king to a safer area.}) 15. Nc4) 14.
O-O-O Bd7 (14... cxd5 {Potkin,V (2594)-Steel,H (2414) Fufeng 2017 (1-0, 38)}
15. cxd5 $1 $16 {could transpose below.}) 15. Kb1 cxd5 16. cxd5 Rc8 {Due to
his slightly premature knight jump to c5, Black has no obvious way of
developing his queenside initiative.} 17. Bb5 {Carrying out a strategically
favourable exchange.} (17. Rc1 $5) (17. h4 $5 Qxh4 $2 18. g5 $1 $18) 17... Bxb5
18. Nxb5 Qd7 19. Nc3 Bf6 20. g5 Bd8 21. h4 Na8 22. Bxc5 Rxc5 23. Qxa4 Qc8 24.
Rc1 Nb6 25. Qd1 Qh3 26. Qf3 Qd7 (26... Qxh4 27. Rg4 Qh5 28. Rh1 $18) 27. Qd3
$16 {Carlsen,M (2772)-Topalov,V (2813) Nanjing 2009 (1-0, 41).} *

