{[%evp 0,41,16,19,30,-11,51,42,35,31,37,47,45,38,49,14,20,20,20,-10,8,-20,25,
18,19,-21,-7,5,7,6,39,26,54,40,122,164,217,226,210,171,177,177,151,163]} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5 a5 8. Be3 Na6 9. g4
Nc5 {With this move Black tries to save time on the maneuver Nf6-d7-c5. In
this case, however, Black will face some serious coordination problems. After
the eventual g4-g5, the d7-square may become overcrowded.} 10. Nd2 c6 ({
Opening the kingside with} 10... Ne8 11. h4 f5 {would only play into White's
hands:} 12. gxf5 gxf5 13. Qe2 Nf6 ({Or} 13... f4 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. Bh3 {
with similar consequences.}) 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. Bh3 {with great play on the
light squares, for instance} fxe4 16. Ndxe4 b6 17. Ng5 $16 {[%cal Gg5e6] soon
invading Black's position via e6, Sulava,N (2320)-Emonts Gast,Y Hamburg 1982 
(1-0, 20)}) 11. Be2 {This is the main line.} ({Another option is} 11. Rg1 {
In this case, Black can go for} a4 $146 {when the play might continue} 12. Bxc5
dxc5 13. Nxa4 Ne8 (13... b5 14. cxb5 cxd5 {is a more dynamic approach.}) 14.
Nxc5 Bh6 {with very unclear play.}) 11... Bd7 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Ga5a4] With
this move, Black prepares the advance a5-a4 without sacrificing a pawn. On the
other hand, the problematic d7-square is already occupied.} (11... cxd5 12.
cxd5 b6 {Black consolidates his knight in order to make the threat Bxc5
strategically less dangerous. But this weakens too many light squares.} (12...
Bd7 {would simply transpose below.}) 13. h4 Ne8 {Anton Guijarro,D (2630)
-Barcenilla,R (2455) Baku 2016 (1-0, 45)} 14. g5 f5 15. h5 Rf7 {[%csl Gf8]
Clearing the f8-square for the bishop in anticipation of h5-h6.} 16. Qc2 Na6 $5
{[%csl Re3][%cal Gf5f4] Threatening ...f5-f4.} 17. hxg6 hxg6 18. f3 f4 19. Bf2
Qxg5 {The only way Black can look for consolation for the strategic problems
on both wings.} 20. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gc3b5,Gd1g1] White has two open
kingside files for his rooks and the c4 and b5 squares for the knights.
Black's extra pawn is not really relevant.}) (11... Ne8 {[%cal Gf7f5] prepares
an early ...f7-f5 but spoils the minor piece coordination.} 12. Nb3 Nd7 {
[%cal Ga5a4,Yd7c5] Hoping to return to c5 after ...a5-a4.} ({But} 12... cxd5
13. cxd5 b6 {is worth considering.}) 13. a4 $5 f5 14. gxf5 gxf5 15. exf5 Ndf6 (
{Black canot activate his back rank knight as} 15... Nef6 $2 16. dxc6 bxc6 17.
Qxd6 {White simply wins an important pawn.}) ({Or if} 15... Rxf5 16. Qd2 {
[%cal Ge1c1,Gh1g1,Gh3h4,Gh4h5,Ge2g4] followed by 0-0-0, Rhg1, h4-h5, possibly
with Bg4 in between, White has a consistent attack almost for free.}) 16. Bd3
Kh8 17. Rg1 Qe7 {In Riazantsev,A (2638)-Svidler,P (2746) Dagomys 2008 (0-1, 25)
which we examined in some detail in the strategic article, the strongest would
have been} 18. Qd2 $5 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh3h4,Gh4h5] planning 0-0-0 followed by the
familiar plan was a safer way to an advantage. If} e4 19. Bc2 {[%cal Gb3d4]
the knight on b3 suddenly proves useful due to the threat Nd4 and if} c5 20.
O-O-O Bxf5 21. f3 $16 {White keeps the better development, safer king and
considerable space advantage.}) ({The next line deals with the more
straightforward} 11... a4) 12. g5 $1 {Since the knight is deprived of the
ideal d7-square, this move becomes logical.} ({If} 12. h4 cxd5 13. cxd5 {
Black is in time to complete his queenside development with} Rc8 $1 {which
remarkably allows him to later move with his knight to h5 when attacked.} 14.
h5 ({Or} 14. g5 Nh5 $1 15. Bxh5 gxh5 16. Bxc5 Rxc5 {Avoiding the spoiling of
the queenside structure.} 17. Qxh5 b5 {[%csl Gd7,Gg7][%cal Gf7f5] Black has
more than enough compensation for the missing pawn. Grischuk, A (2751)
-Naiditsch,A (2686) Novi Sad 2016 (0-1, 45).}) 14... b5 ({Surely better than} 
14... gxh5 {as played in two games.}) 15. hxg6 ({Better than} 15. g5 $6 Nxh5 $1
16. Bxc5 Rxc5 17. Bxh5 b4 {White has serious problems. The only way to keep
the queen on its track to h5 is} 18. Ncb1 {but this offers Black huge
initiative for the piece after} Qxg5 {[%cal Gf8c8] followed by ...Rfc8.}) 15...
fxg6 16. g5 Nh5 17. Rxh5 $5 ({More ambitious than} 17. Bxh5 b4 {when the
familiar} 18. Ncb1 $2 {loses outright to} Nd3+ 19. Kf1 ({Or} 19. Ke2 Nxb2 {
[%cal Gd7b5]}) 19... Rc1) 17... b4 18. Nb5 gxh5 19. Nxd6 Ba4 20. b3 Qxd6 {
White surely has compensation for the exchange, but the position is quite
messy.}) 12... Ne8 (12... Nh5 {leaves Black with chronic problems on light
squares all over the board.} 13. Bxc5 dxc5 14. Bxh5 gxh5 15. Qxh5 {And it
loses a pawn, of course.} a4 16. a3 Ra6 17. O-O-O b5 {Just making things worse
as more light squares become available to White.} 18. dxc6 b4 19. Nd5 Rxc6 20.
Nf3 bxa3 21. bxa3 Kh8 22. Nf6 Bxf6 23. gxf6 $18 {Vega Gutierrez,S (2373)-Injac,
T (2277) Novi Sad 2017 (1-0, 40)}) 13. h4 cxd5 {If Black intends to open the
c-file he should exchange on d5 as soon as possible in order to avoid giving
