19. hxg6 hxg6 20. Bg4 {with a big advantage.}) (15... cxd5 16. Nxd5 $1 {
The point is that with his kingside weakened Black has problems carrying out
the plan of bringing a knight on e6:} Nc7 17. Nb6 Rb8 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 19. exf5
$16 gxf5 $6 {This strategically consistent move, keeping the control over the
e4-square, runs into a decisive attack:} 20. h6 Bh8 21. Bh5 Re7 22. g6) 16.
O-O-O cxd5 17. Nxd5 $14 {Morozov,N (2429)-Giannoulakis,L (2287) Rio Achaea
2018 (0-1, 34)}) (13... f6 14. Nb3 $1 {Exchanging Black's only active piece.}
b6 15. Nxc5 bxc5 16. Qd2 fxg5 17. hxg5 cxd5 18. Nxd5 Rf7 19. O-O-O {Black was
doomed to passivity in Anand,V (2785)-Ponomariov,R (2717) Bilbao 2014 (1-0, 61)
.}) (13... Nc7 {looks like a "fluent" continuation, but does not parry White's
slow plan.} 14. h5 Re8 {Preparing to answer h5-h6 with ...Bf8.} ({With the
c7-knight far from the e4-square,} 14... cxd5 {is best met with} 15. exd5 $1 {
preventing ... b7-b5 and keeping the control on e4.} N7a6 16. Nde4 Bf5 17. f3
a4 18. Qd2 $16 {Adhiban,B (2515)-Thipsay,P (2465) New Delhi 2010 (½-½, 91)})
15. hxg6 hxg6 16. Kf1 N7a6 17. a3 a4 18. Kg2 cxd5 19. cxd5 b5 20. Na2 Rc8 21.
Rh4 Kf8 22. Rh7 {White's advantage is obvious, but Black continues to find
resources.} Ke7 $5 23. Bxb5 $1 (23. Rxg7 $6 Rh8 {[%csl Rg7] traps the rook,
for instance} 24. Bxb5 Kf8 $1) (23. Nc3 {maintained some advantage to White,
but Black's position became playable already.} Rh8 24. Qh1 Rxh7 25. Qxh7 Kf8
26. f4 exf4 27. Bxf4 Qe7 28. Rf1 b4 {with certain counterplay in Raznikov,D 
(2474)-Kozul,Z (2608) Skopje 2013 (0-1, 35)}) 23... Bxb5 24. Rxg7 Rh8 25. Qf3
$18) 14. cxd5 ({With the kingside solid,} 14. Nxd5 Nc7 {is absolutely fine for
Black.}) ({Or if} 14. exd5 Bf5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc5d3] controlling e4 and
threatening ...Nd3+.}) 14... f5 (14... Rb8 {is best met with} 15. a4 $1 {
Freezing Black's queenside.} (15. h5 b5 {looks reasonable for Black.}) ({Or if
} 15. Nc4 {[%cal Gc4d6]} Rc8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5] Preventing Nxd6 and renewing the
threat ...b7-b5.} 16. a4 f5 17. gxf6 {More or less forced since e4 is poorly
defended now.} Bxf6 18. h5 Bg5 19. hxg6 hxg6 20. Qc1 Bf4 {with reasonable play
for Black in Olbrich-Makropoulou, Yerevan 1996.}) 15... f6 (15... f5 {allows}
16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. Nc4 {with a firm contol on light squares.}) 16. h5 fxg5 17.
hxg6 h6 18. Nc4 b6 19. Rb1 {Black has defended his kingside, but problems are
awaiting him on the opposite wing.}) (14... a4 15. a3 (15. h5 $5) 15... Rc8 {
Bellahcene,B (2496)-Bacrot,E (2689) London 2016 (1/2, 61)} 16. h5) (14... Nc7 {
takes the knight farther from the d6-square, making} 15. Bxc5 dxc5 16. a4 $16 {
[%cal Gd2c4] followed by Nc4 a reasonable change of plan.}) 15. h5 Rf7 {
Black is best adviced to clear the f8-square for the bishop, otherwise h5-h6
may force him to play the rest of the game with a piece down. But the rook is
vulnerable now} (15... f4 16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. h6 Bh8 18. Bg4 Ra6 19. Na4 Bxg4 20.
Qxg4 Qe7 21. Rc1 $18 {Schoehuys,E (2180)-Majhi,A (2058) Groningen 2013 (1-0,
31)}) (15... Rc8 16. h6 Bh8 17. Rg1 b5 18. Nxb5 fxe4 19. Bxc5 Rxc5 20. Nc3 e3
21. fxe3 e4 22. Ndxe4 Rc8 23. Bg4 $16 {Loiseau,Q (2354)-Bailet,P (2485)
Sautron 2014 (1-0, 48)}) 16. hxg6 hxg6 17. exf5 Bxf5 (17... gxf5 {offers White
a strong attack:} 18. Bh5 Re7 19. Bg6 Nd3+ 20. Kf1 Rc8 21. Qh5 Nxb2 22. Nce4 $1
{White is attacking with almost all of his pieces already.} fxe4 23. Nxe4 Nd3
24. Rd1 Nf4 25. Bxf4 exf4 26. Rh4 $18) 18. Nf1 (18. Rh4 Rc8 19. Nde4 $14 {
is a reasonable alternative.}) 18... a4 19. Ng3 a3 20. b4 e4 21. bxc5 Bxc3+ 22.
