{[%evp 0,45,19,31,14,-11,43,42,40,38,37,54,42,47,28,27,40,18,30,-4,16,-29,5,17,
31,11,34,-3,74,50,44,68,85,24,85,102,102,44,58,11,57,48,48,33,60,77,100,112]} 
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5 a5 8. Be3 Na6
9. g4 Nc5 10. Nd2 c6 11. Be2 a4 {Black sacrifices a pawn in order to eliminate
White's strong dark-squared bishop and free the a5-square for his queen. Of
course, White is not forced to take the pawn.} 12. a3 {With this move, White
indicates his intentions to play on the kingside. Also, we can say that the
inclusion of the moves a2-a3 and a5-a4 slows Black's play down.} ({I have also
dealt with} 12. g5 Nfd7 13. h4 Qa5 {[%cal Ga4a3,Yc5a6,Ya6b4,Yd7c5,Yb2b3]
Threatening ...a4-a3 and after b2-b3 ...Na6-b4, ...Nc5, with certain pressure.}
14. a3 f5 15. f3 (15. h5 f4 16. Bxc5 Nxc5 17. h6 Bh8 {Despite the fact that
Black is practically playing without a bishop, the position is far from clear
since White's king is not safe in the center.} 18. Bf3) 15... cxd5 (15... fxe4
16. fxe4 Rf4 17. h5) 16. cxd5 b5 {1/2 (35) Bosiocic,M (2611)-Jones,G (2651)
Batumi 2018} 17. O-O Ba6 18. Na2 $14) ({Accepting the pawn(s) does not seem to
suit White's strategic approach in this line:} 12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. Nxa4 Bh6 14.
Nxc5 Qb6 {with adequate Black counterplay in Leitao-Morozevich, Tromsoe 2013})
({The alternate move order for Riazantsev's plan is} 12. Kf1 Qa5 ({The attempt
to stabilize the queenside with} 12... a3 13. b4 Na6 14. Rb1 c5 15. bxc5 Nxc5 {
does not seem to offer Black an easy life due to his weaknesses along the
b-file.}) 13. a3 {and we are back in the game.}) (12. Rb1 $5 {also deserves
some attention.}) 12... Qa5 13. Kf1 cxd5 ({With his queen far from the
kingside, Black should refrain from weakening his king with} 13... Nfd7 14. h4
f5 $6 15. gxf5 gxf5 16. exf5 Nf6 17. h5 h6 18. Rg1 $16) 14. cxd5 Bd7 (14...
Nfd7 15. Nc4 $16) 15. h4 b5 {The play becomes double-edged since both players
are attacking on opposite wings. In such positions, White's attack is usually
going faster.} 16. h5 $1 (16. g5 {runs into} Nh5 $1 17. Bxh5 gxh5 18. Qxh5 b4
19. axb4 Qxb4 {when Black has a nice compensation for the pawn.}) 16... Rfb8 {
Black is now prepared to retreat his knight to e8.} (16... Rab8 {is abstractly
less accurate as the knight will soon stand between the rooks.} 17. g5 Ne8 18.
Na2 Qd8 19. Nb4 Nc7 20. Bg4 Be8 21. Qf3 f5 22. gxf6 Bxf6 23. hxg6 hxg6 24. Ke2
Bg7 25. Qh3 $18 {Martinovic,S (2550)-Lanka,Z (2439) Germany 2016 (1-0, 35)}) (
16... b4 {runs into} 17. Nc4 Qc7 18. axb4 Ncxe4 (18... Nb3 19. h6 Bh8 20. Bb6
Qb7 21. Ra3 Rac8 22. g5 Nxe4 {A desperate attempt to change the course of
events.} ({If} 22... Ne8 23. Nxa4) 23. Nxe4 Rxc4 24. Bxc4 Qxb6 25. Bxb3 axb3
26. Qf3 $16 {White is an exchange up and keeps the position firm in his hand.})
19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. Nb6 Rab8 {Kozionov,K (2461)-Amonatov,F (2615) St Petersburg
2018 (0-1, 47)} 21. Nxd7 Qxd7 22. b5 f5 23. Qxa4 $16) (16... Rac8 {does not
contribute to the main plan too much.} 17. g5 Ne8 18. hxg6 fxg6 19. Kg2 Rf7 20.
Rh4 Bf8 21. Qh1 Rb8 22. Na2 Qd8 23. Qh2 Na6 24. Rh1 Qe7 25. Nf3 $16 {Lysyj,I 
(2638)-Stubberud,O (2293) Plovdiv 2010 (1-0, 43)}) (16... Rfc8 17. g5 Ne8 18.
Kg2 Rab8 {is a slower version of the main continuation.} 19. Na2 Nc7 20. hxg6
hxg6 21. Rh4 Rb7 (21... Nb3 $2 22. Nxb3 axb3 23. Qxb3 $18 {Lopez Martinez,J 
(2581)-Perez Ponsa,F (2554) Barcelona 2018 (1-0, 62)}) 22. Qh1 Ne8 23. Nb4 $16)
17. g5 Ne8 18. hxg6 hxg6 19. Na2 $1 {Suddenly, Black needs some more time to
prepare his queenside break. Now is when the move a2-a3 proves very useful.}
Nc7 20. Kg2 N7a6 21. Rh4 f5 $2 {This surely makes things only worse, but Black
was in trouble already.} ({If} 21... b4 22. Qh1 {[%cal Gh4h7] followed by Rh7
White would anyway have a devastating attack.}) 22. gxf6 Bxf6 23. Qh1 $1 {
with a decisive attack in Riazantsev, A (2646)-Kokarev, D (2630) Ulan Ude 2009
(1-0, 31).} *

