{[%evp 0,59,19,19,25,-14,49,33,46,46,46,33,43,29,34,14,38,32,44,45,43,5,81,49,
45,34,53,-21,-2,11,74,40,38,21,21,21,21,10,2,-35,9,22,19,18,18,26,26,28,17,23,
23,23,13,0,64,97,116,110,139,133,130,135]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4
d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5 Nh5 {If it wasn't for its popularity at a high
level, I would consider this move the fruit of childish impatience. Black
tries to start the kingside attack with incomplete development. True, his
threats could become annoying if not met adequately. And after going through
the practical material available, I would conclude that this line suits the
King's Indian spirit best by allowing Black to fish in muddy waters. What also
makes the last move attractive is the prevention of an early g2-g4, as the
knight would happily jump to f4, even at the cost of one pawn.} 8. g3 {It is
important to understand this subtle positional move. After preventing Black's.
..Nf4, White is planning to gradually drive the knight back to f6. Such an
idea can be realized by means of simple moves such as Be2, Be3, and Nd2. That
is the reason why Black usually goes for the quick f7-f5 advance. White is
advised to answer this advance with exf5 and castle long. Even though Black's
f5 and e5 pawns control a number of important squares, in many positions, they
can prove vulnerable. White usually tries to provoke the advance of one of
these pawns and then make use of the weakened dark or light squares. A typical
way to put pressure would be the advance g3-g4. Another idea to attack the
f5-pawn is to play simple moves like Bd3, Qc2, and Nh4 (or even Ng5).} f5 {
The most straightforward continuation, but Black has tried a wide range of
other moves, which we will examine separately.} 9. exf5 gxf5 10. Nh4 {[%csl
Rf5] We can see another merit of the move g2-g3. The pressure against the
f5-pawn can become unpleasant.} Nf4 {The most ambitious move, even though the
knight's stability is precarious here.} ({The alternative is} 10... Nf6 11. Bd3
{Forcing Black to weaken the dark squares.} ({The seemingly active} 11. Bg5 {
actually helps Black to clear the h7-square for his knight:} Na6 12. Bd3 h6 13.
Be3 Nh7 {as in Tomashevsky,E (2716)-Radjabov,T (2731) Tbilisi 2015 (1/2, 31).})
11... e4 12. Be2 Na6 (12... Nfd7 13. Ng2 Ne5 14. Nf4 Na6 15. Be3 Nc5 16. O-O
Ng6 17. Qd2 {White has achieved very pleasant stability in the center and
Black's next move creates worries for himself.} Nxf4 18. gxf4 $1 a5 19. Kh2 Kh8
20. Rg1 {[%cal Gg1g7] with dangerous threats along the g-file,
Nisipeanu-Vedmediuc, Calimanesti 2014.}) 13. Bg5 (13. Ng2) (13. Be3 Nc5 14. Qd2
Nfd7 15. Bg5 Bf6 16. Bh6 Ne5 17. Bxf8 Qxf8 {offered Black good compensation in
Granda Zuniga,J (2646)-Strikovic,A (2522) La Roda 2015 (1-0, 44)}) 13... h6 (
13... Qe8 14. Ng2 Nc5 15. O-O Nfd7 16. Nb5) 14. Be3 Nd7 15. Qd2 Kh7 16. Ng2 $14
) (10... Qe8 11. Be2 {transposes to 8...Qe8.}) 11. Bd2 {It is best to leave
Black with permanent worries regarding his knight.} (11. gxf4 {is unclear:}
Qxh4 12. fxe5 (12. Rg1 Nd7 13. Nb5 exf4 14. Nxc7 {In Cheparinov,I (2690)-Vovk,
Y (2591) Warsaw 2014 (1-0, 27) Black would have retained sufficient
compensation for the material with} Ne5 15. Nxa8 Re8 16. Rxg7+ {Necessary in
order to avoid losing the rook after Kd2, ...Qxf2+.} Kxg7 17. Kd2 Qxf2+ 18. Kc3
Nf3 {with a possible draw by perpetual.}) 12... Nd7 $1 13. e6 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3
Qe4+ 15. Be3 Qxh1 16. Qh5 Ne5 17. e7 Bd7 18. exf8=Q+ Rxf8 19. Qg5+ Kf7 {
Sooner or later White would have to deliver perpetual check as his king is
also exposed.} 20. O-O-O Ba4 21. Qxf5+ (21. Re1 Qe4 $17) 21... Kg8 22. Qe6+ Rf7
23. Re1 Bd7 24. Qh6 Bf5 25. Qg5+ Bg6 26. Bd4 Nd3+ 27. Bxd3 Qxe1+ 28. Kb2 Qe7
29. Qg3 Kf8 30. Bxg6 hxg6 31. Qxg6 $11) ({I prefer 11.Bd2 over} 11. Be3 {
because in the following line the bishop is exposed on e3:} Ng6 $1 $146 {
Never tried in practice.} 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Qd2 f4 $1 14. gxf4 exf4 15. Bxf4
Nd7 16. O-O-O Qh4 17. Bg3 Qh6 18. Bd3 Nc5 19. Bc2 Qh5 20. Rhe1 Bf5 {With
adequate compensation for the pawn.}) 11... Qe7 (11... Na6 {places the knight
far from e5, allowing} 12. gxf4 $1 (12. a3 Nc5 13. Qc2 a5 {was reasonable for
Black in Gonzalez Vidal, Y (2555)-Morovic Fernandez, I (2572) Varadero 2016 
(1-0, 36)}) 12... Qxh4 13. fxe5 Bxe5 (13... dxe5 14. Rg1 $14) 14. Rg1+ Kh8 15.
Bg5 Qd4 16. Qxd4 Bxd4 17. O-O-O Bxf2 (17... Bg7 18. Re1 $14 {also leaves White
better developed.}) 18. Rg2 Bb6 19. Re1 $16 {with a huge advance in
development for the pawn.}) ({Black cannot keep the knight close to e5 after} 
11... Nd7 12. Qc2 {[%csl Rf5] Attacking f5.} Nc5 {Shkalov,O (2239)-Hakobyan,H 
(2043) St Petersburg 2015 (0-1, 37)} 13. b4 Na6 14. a3 $14) 12. Qc2 Na6 13. a3
Bd7 14. O-O-O Kh8 15. Kb1 Rae8 16. Re1 Qf6 17. Rg1 $14 {So far, both players
have displayed admirable patience but now Black could not stand the pressure
anymore.} Ng6 ({He could have maintained the tension with} 17... Nc5 {even
though his exposed king's position would have left him with permanent worries.
White should play} 18. b4 {forcing the knight to retreat onto the passive
a6-square.}) 18. Nxg6+ Qxg6 ({Black's initial intention might have been} 18...
hxg6 {In fact, this move does not consolidate the kingside. On the contrary,
it allows White to start an attack with} 19. h4 Nc5 (19... c6 20. Bg5 Qf7 21.
h5) 20. b4 (20. Bg5 Qf7 21. h5 f4 22. hxg6 Qf5) 20... Ne4 21. Nxe4 fxe4 22. Be3
$16) 19. f3 c6 (19... e4 20. f4 $14 Bd4 21. Be3 Qf6 22. Bxd4 Qxd4 23. Be2 {
planning b2-b4 and g3-g4.}) 20. g4 {with dangerous initiative Tomashevsky, E 
(2716)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2705) Tbilisi 2015 (1-0, 30)} *

