23,23,13,0,64,97,116,110,139,133,130,135]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4
d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5 Nh5 8. g3 f5 9. exf5 gxf5 10. Nh4 Nf4 11. Bd2 {
The untested} Ng6 $5 $146 {requires detailed examining.} 12. Nxg6 hxg6 {
Engines are very skeptical about Black's position at this height, but things
are not that simple. It took some effort to find the best move orders for
White.} 13. h4 {White will try to play h4-h5 in such a way that Black cannot
answer with ...g6-g5.} Nd7 (13... Na6 {places the knight too far from e5
allowing White to speed up his attack on the light squares.} 14. Qe2 Qe7 15.
O-O-O Bd7 16. h5 g5 17. g4 $16) (13... e4 {prevents f2-f4 in the main line,
but weakens the dark squares too early, allowing White to define his plans.}
14. Qc1 Bf6 (14... Nd7 15. h5 Ne5 16. Be2 {also offers White the initiative.})
15. Ne2 $1 Nd7 16. Nf4 Ne5 17. Be2 Bd7 18. Bc3 $14 {[%cal Ge1f1,Gf1g2] After
stabilizing the position White could transfer his king to g2 and then combine
threats on both wings.} Qe8 19. Kf1 a5 (19... c5 20. Kg2 a6 21. b4 $16) 20. Kg2
b6 21. Qd2 Qf7 22. b3 Qg7 23. Rac1 Rfe8 24. a3 $14) 14. Bg5 ({A typical line
in which the engines' enthusiasm is gradually going down is} 14. h5 g5 15. h6
Bf6 16. Qc2 e4 17. g4 Ne5 18. Be2 Qe7 19. O-O-O Qh7 {with good play for Black.}
) 14... Bf6 (14... Nf6 {offers White the freedom to choose the right moment of
breaking with h4-h5 and/or g3-g4.:}) 15. f4 $3 {A "handmade" move.} ({If} 15.
Qd2 e4 16. O-O-O Ne5 17. Be2 {[%cal Gg3g4]} Bxg5 18. hxg5 Nf7 19. Kb1 Qxg5 20.
Qd4 Qe7 {White has just reasonable compensation for the pawn. The recommended
move stabilizes the center and makes h4-h5 unstoppable in the long run.}) 15...
Re8 16. Kd2 Nc5 (16... e4 17. Kc2 a6 18. Be2 Nc5 19. h5 $16) (16... exf4 17.
gxf4 Qe7 18. Kc2 $14) 17. Kc2 $14 {Black's chances to open the kingside are
higher than Black's prospects for counterplay. For instance:} Bd7 18. Qd2 a5
19. Re1 Kg7 20. fxe5 Rxe5 21. Rxe5 dxe5 22. Bh6+ Kf7 23. Be3 b6 24. h5 g5 25.
g4 *

