{[%evp 0,35,19,31,14,-14,43,32,42,45,37,40,43,36,63,13,58,30,39,19,59,50,47,36,
37,38,21,-11,2,-2,96,75,71,116,116,82,120,86]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4.
e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5 Nh5 8. g3 {Since the benefits of an early
attack with ...f7-f5 are far from clear, Black can also think of preparing it.
We will start with two ways of developing the queenside.} a5 {But after the
important commitment involved by the knight jump, this move is a bit slow.} 9.
Be3 f5 {Alternating moves on the opposite wings looks a bit inconsequent, but
Black should not delay his counterplay for too long. Black relies on the fact
that the bishop may be exposed on e3.} ({If} 9... Na6 10. Nd2 Bd7 ({
совсем крутая партия мяу!} 10... Nf6 11. g4 Nd7 12. a3 Nb6
13. h4 Bd7 14. Qf3 Nc5 15. h5 Bf6 16. Qh3 g5 17. Be2 a4 18. O-O $16 {1-0 (40)
Jakovenko,D (2712)-Kovalenko,I (2667) Poikovsky 2016}) 11. Be2 Nf6 (11... f5
12. exf5 gxf5 13. Bxh5 f4 14. Nde4 fxe3 15. fxe3 Bh6 16. Qe2 $16 {Vojinovic,G 
(2460)-Pantelic,S (2312) Paracin 2014 (1-0, 45)}) 12. g4 {Black simply loses a
tempo over the similar variations. In the following game Black went down
rather quickly:} c6 13. h4 cxd5 14. cxd5 Qb8 15. g5 Ne8 16. Nc4 Qd8 17. Bb6 Qe7
18. Nxa5 $16 {with an advantage for White on both wings, Wang, H (2710)-Bacrot,
E (2718) Beijing (rapid, Basque) 2014 (1-0, 36)}) 10. exf5 gxf5 11. Nh4 ({
The main alternative is as usual} 11. Ng5) 11... Nf4 {Once again this jump
forward looks like the critical move. But the tempo Black spent on ...a7-a5
allows White to stay in control.} (11... Nf6 {allows White to block the
queenside in his favor:} 12. Bd3 e4 13. Be2 $14) ({A principled move would be} 
11... f4 {immediately attacking the exposed bishop. But it does not seem to
work out well:} 12. Qxh5 fxe3 13. Bd3 exf2+ 14. Kf1 h6 15. Qg6 Rf6 16. Qh7+ Kf8
17. Ne4 {with a decisive attack.}) ({Or if} 11... Qe8 12. Be2 ({Starting the
fight for the light squares with} 12. Nxf5 {looks a bit premature:} Bxf5 13. g4
Nf4 14. gxf5 Nd7 15. Rg1 Kh8 16. Ne4 Qf7 17. Qc2 Qxf5 18. Rg5 Qf7 19. O-O-O Bh6
20. Rg3 Qh5 21. Kb1 b6 {[%cal Gd7c5] followed by ...Nc5. Both sides are stable
and it is not easy for White to prove an advantage.}) 12... Nf6 13. Qc2 Na6 14.
a3 Bd7 15. Rg1 Kh8 16. O-O-O Nc5 17. g4 $11 {After completing the development,
the time has come to start fighting for the light squares.}) 12. Qd2 {Just as
in line 5, it is better to keep the capture on f4 in reserve.} ({If} 12. gxf4
Qxh4 13. Rg1 exf4 ({Better than} 13... Qe7 14. Be2 Nd7 15. Qd2 Rf6 16. Nb5 exf4
17. Bxf4 Ne5 18. O-O-O $16 {Ushenina, A (2452)-Ju, W (2501) Khanty-Mansiysk
2012 (½-½, 28)}) 14. Qd4 Rf6 15. Qxf4 Qxf4 16. Bxf4 Na6 {with normal play
for Black.}) 12... Na6 (12... Ng6 {practically offers White an extra tempo
over line 6, as ...a7-a5 is not useful for the kingside fight:} 13. Nxg6 hxg6
14. O-O-O Nd7 15. h4 Bf6 (15... e4 16. h5 $18) 16. f4 $16) 13. O-O-O Bd7 14.
gxf4 {Time has come to release the tension.} Qxh4 15. Rg1 Rae8 16. Ne2 $1 {
The knight joins the fight for the dark squares.} Nc5 (16... a4 17. fxe5 dxe5
18. f4 $14) 17. fxe5 Rxe5 18. Bd4 Ba4 $5 {The best tactical chance.} 19. Rxg7+
(19. b3 Bxb3 $1) 19... Kxg7 20. f4 Bxd1 21. Qxd1 Nd7 22. Bc3 Rg8 23. fxe5 dxe5
24. b3 $14 {The position remains double-edged but White's bishops put the
enemy king in permanent danger.} *

