{[%evp 0,47,27,25,27,0,40,46,32,32,32,50,50,31,35,15,49,32,40,23,57,59,36,37,
-13,6,-4,-11,-16,12,25,25,64,-16,-21,-17,-31,-14,-24,-19,-27,-10,-5,-79,91,61,
61,49,33,73]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5
Nh5 8. g3 Na6 {This leads to more rapid development than in line 7 but the
knight will have to choose a good moment to jump to c5 in order to avoid
running into b2-b4.} 9. Be3 Qe8 {Black over-defends the h5-knight indirectly,
in order to keep the kingside break in reserve until White makes a commitment.}
(9... Nc5 {has been played more than once, but after} 10. Nd2 a5 11. Be2 Nf6
12. g4 {White just gains a tempo over the normal lines. Black has wasted two
tempi with his knight while White has done so only once with his g-pawn.}) (
9... f5 {is examined in line 9.}) 10. Be2 ({With the queen on e8} 10. Nd2 {
fails to achieve the same as in the line above due to} f5) 10... f5 ({Black
cannot wait anymore as after} 10... Nc5 11. Nd2 f5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. g4 $16 {
[%csl Rf5,Rh5] he loses a piece with no obvious compensation.}) 11. exf5 gxf5
12. Nh4 Nf6 {In order to continue his development, White has to choose the
best square for the queen. Not an easy task as both on c2 and d2 she could get
under the enemy knights' attack.} 13. Qd2 $1 {On d2, the queen ensures White
better stability at an early stage. And since he still is a few tempi away
from castling, it is better to avoid the early attack ...Nb4. Later, he will
find a way to deal with ...Ne4.} ({If} 13. Qc2 f4 $1 14. gxf4 exf4 15. Bd4 f3
$1 {This is the right move order, yielding Black strong initiative.} ({After} 
15... Nb4 $2 16. Qd2 f3 {Black ran into} 17. Rg1 $1 $16 {Parligras,M (2614)
-Fressinet,L (2693) Plovdiv 2012 (0-1, 47).}) 16. Nxf3 Nb4 17. Qd2 Bf5 {
with strong initiative.}) 13... Nc5 ({It is easy to understand that with the
queen on d2 already} 13... f4 {does not work:} 14. gxf4 exf4 15. Bd4 f3 {
This was played in a couple of games, but none of them continued with} 16. Rg1
$1 $146 {when} fxe2 $2 {loses to} 17. Rxg7+ Kxg7 18. Qg5+) 14. O-O-O a6 {
Black prepares his standard queenside counterplay.} ({The gain of time after} 
14... Nfe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Qc2 {[%csl Re4] is deceiving as the central
knight is hanging.} c6 (16... Qf7 17. g4 f4 18. Qxe4 fxe3 19. Bd3 Bf6 20. g5 {
both with a strategic advantage as well as an attack.}) 17. g4 cxd5 {
Ivanisevic,I (2664)-Hausrath,D (2491) Biel 2008 (0-1, 29)} 18. Rxd5 Nf6 19.
Rxd6 Qe7 20. Rdd1 f4 21. Bd2 $18) (14... Na4 {deserves mentioning, too. But
White has a simple way to slow down Black's counterattack.} 15. Nxa4 $146 Qxa4
16. Kb1 b5 17. cxb5 a6 18. b6 $1 {Keeping the queenside closed.} cxb6 19. f3
Bd7 20. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gg3g4] followed by g3-g4 soon.}) 15. g4 {A positional
and attacking move at the same time. White fights for the light squares but
also hopes to open the h- or the g-file.} b5 {A desperate attempt at
counterplay.} (15... fxg4 16. hxg4 Nxg4 17. Bxg4 Bxg4 18. Rdg1 {offers White a
devastating attack.}) 16. cxb5 axb5 17. Bxc5 {Switching to the strategic mode.}
dxc5 18. Bxb5 Qf7 19. Nxf5 Bxf5 20. gxf5 {White has won two pawns and has
crushing domination on the light squares. Curiously, the game Khairullin, I 
(2630)-Mamedov, R (2658) Moscow 2015 (½-½, 23) ended in a draw four moves
later.} *

