{[%evp 0,47,27,25,27,0,40,46,32,32,32,50,50,31,35,15,49,32,40,23,57,59,36,37,
-13,6,-4,-11,-16,12,25,25,64,-16,-21,-17,-31,-14,-24,-19,-27,-10,-5,-79,91,61,
61,49,33,73]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5
Nh5 8. g3 Na6 9. Be3 f5 {From a development point of view,, this is an
improved version of line 7, as ...Na6 is more useful (at least short term)
than ...a7-a5.} 10. exf5 gxf5 11. Qd2 $5 {This move was played only once, but
I find it very strong. White keeps developing naturally, ignoring the obvious
threat ...f5-f4. At the same time he maintains the flexibility regarding the
choice between Nh4 and Ng5.} ({The most popular move is} 11. Ng5) ({White's
attempt to transpose to familiar paths with} 11. Nh4 Nf6 12. Bd3 {runs into} f4
13. gxf4 exf4 14. Bd4 Nb4 15. Rg1 {Alonso Rosell,A (2537)-Pablo Marin,A (2383)
Barcelona 2017 (1-0, 59)} c5 $1 $146 16. dxc6 Nxc6 {and White has to part with
his dark-squared bishop, offering Black counterplay along the long diagonal.})
11... f4 {It is hard to refrain from this move, of course.} ({But it is worth
investigating the developing} 11... Nc5 12. O-O-O a5 ({As in other lines,
transferring a knight to e4 leaves Black hanging:} 12... Nf6 13. Qc2 Nfe4 14.
Nxe4 Nxe4 15. h4 Bd7 16. h5 h6 17. Nh4 $14) 13. Rg1 {[%cal Gg3g4] White
prepares g3-g4.} Nf6 (13... Bd7 {plays into White's hands:} 14. g4 fxg4 15.
hxg4 Nf4 16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. g5 Bf5 18. Nh4 Qd7 19. Qe3 $16 {[%cal Gh4f5,Yc3e4]
planning Nxf5 followed by Ne4.}) 14. Ng5 {White finally makes his choice
regarding the knight jump.} h6 15. Ne6 Nxe6 16. dxe6 h5 {Defending the h-pawn
and taking measures against g3-g4.} 17. f3 Bxe6 18. g4 $14 {White has a very
dangerous initiative for the pawn. For instance:} hxg4 19. hxg4 f4 20. Bf2 e4
21. Bd4 $1 e3 $2 22. Qh2 $18 {[%cal Gf1d3] followed by Bd3 with a decisive
attack.}) 12. gxf4 Nxf4 (12... exf4 13. Bd4 $16) 13. Rg1 Kh8 14. O-O-O {
It appears that despite his strong knight on f4, Black has problems along the
g-file and on the light squares.} Qe8 (14... Nd3+ $2 15. Bxd3 Rxf3 16. Ne4 $18
{offers White a winning attack.}) (14... Nc5 $5 {is an improved version of the
same plan.} 15. b4 Ncd3+ (15... Nd7 16. Ng5 Nf6 17. Bxf4 exf4 18. Bd3 $16) (
15... Na6 16. a3 $16 {[%csl Ra6] isolates the knight.}) 16. Bxd3 Nxd3+ 17. Qxd3
Rxf3 18. Rxg7 $1 Kxg7 19. Bh6+ Kxh6 20. Qxf3 Qg5+ 21. Kb2 Bf5 22. Nb5 $14 {
White wins a queenside pawn, after which his majority will be dangerous in any
endgame.}) 15. Ng5 Bf5 (15... Nc5 16. Nb5 Qe7 17. Re1 a6 18. Nc3 $16) 16. Bxf4
exf4 17. Bd3 $16 {[%cal Gg5e6] White will soon place a knight on e6, Heimann,
A (2557)-Andersen,M (2467) Biel 2015 (1-0, 26)} *

