{[%evp 0,45,30,29,21,-20,51,35,61,59,37,34,44,42,73,15,47,30,57,26,72,74,31,31,
14,11,-3,15,14,14,5,-40,-13,-32,16,18,-10,-10,24,32,46,-6,29,47,21,48,69,66]} 
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5 Nh5 8. g3 Qe8
{We have noticed that the pawn break is usually combined with a queen move to
the e-file. Black can try to achieve increased flexibility by moving with the
queen before defining his other plans.} 9. Be2 {[%csl Rh5] Immediately
starting to build up the pressure against the h5-knight.} f5 (9... Na6 10. Be3
{[%cal Gf3d2] planning Nd2} f5 11. exf5 gxf5 12. Nh4 {would transpose to 9...
Qe8 in the line 8.}) 10. exf5 gxf5 11. Nh4 Nf6 12. Qc2 {A necessary commitment.
} ({White cannot hope to transpose to line 7 with} 12. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2]
followed by Qd2 since Black has a better move than 12...Na6, namely} f4 13.
gxf4 exf4 {with strong counterplay when} 14. Bxf4 Ne4 {is simply bad for White.
}) 12... Na6 (12... e4 $6 {is an unjustified concession, offering White the
control of the dark squares.} 13. Be3 Na6 14. O-O-O Nd7 15. Qd2 Qf7 16. f3 exf3
17. Nxf3 Ne5 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. Bh6 Bg7 20. Rdf1 Bd7 21. Bd3 $16 {Parligras,M 
(2650)-Can,E (2465) Porto Carras 2011 (1-0, 36)}) 13. a3 $1 {[%csl Ra6] A
typical way of restricting the knight.} ({The f5-pawn is indirectly defended:} 
13. Nxf5 Bxf5 14. Qxf5 Nxd5) 13... Nc5 (13... c6 {is strongly met with} 14.
dxc6 $1 Qxc6 ({If} 14... bxc6 {as played in Harika-Ju, Lopota 2014, White
could simply take the pawn with} 15. Nxf5 Bxf5 16. Qxf5 {since there is no
more white pawn hanging on d5.}) 15. O-O f4 16. g4 Nc5 {In Barbot, P (2413)
-Biolek, R (2418) Ruzomberok 2014 (1-0, 61) White's best way to strengthen the
control over the weakened black position would have been} 17. Rd1 Kh8 (17...
Ne6 18. Nf5 {attacks on d6.}) 18. Bf1 $14 {[%cal Gf1g2] planning Bg2.}) 14. Be3
Bd7 {This position was reached in a few games. Optically, Black is well
developed, but White is perfectly regrouped for launching his standard attack:}
15. g4 $1 $146 ({In principle, the idea of} 15. Bxc5 dxc5 16. Nxf5 Bxf5 17.
Qxf5 {needs to be permanently taken into account, but here it seems to offer
relatively little.} Nxd5 18. Qe4 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Qg6 20. Bd3 {In Holt, C (2574)
-Bregadze, L (2435) Orlando 2014 (1-0, 54) Black exchanged on e4 and landed
into an unpleasant endgame, but stronger would have been} Rad8 21. Qxg6 hxg6
22. Bxg6 e4 {with chances to balance the position dynamically.}) 15... fxg4 16.
hxg4 Nxg4 {Grabbing the molesting pawn.} ({If} 16... e4 17. Bxc5 dxc5 18. Nf5
$16 {Black is under serious pressure.}) 17. Bxg4 Bxg4 18. f3 Bd7 {Necessary in
order to allow ...Na4 in case of emergency.} 19. Bxc5 dxc5 20. O-O-O {White is
a pawn down but his knights will soon dominate the position, while the black
king is exposed. For instance} a5 21. Rdg1 Ra6 22. Ne4 Qe7 23. Qh2 $16 {
when Black would not have obvious ways of freeing his position.} *

