{[%evp 0,37,19,38,32,4,51,44,33,37,37,37,27,26,52,15,60,38,64,5,-1,4,16,-25,
-20,-25,-26,-36,0,3,16,0,61,52,73,56,52,45,123,34]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5 Nh5 8. g3 Qe7 $5 {This move, introduced
by Grischuk in top-level practice, induces some major (though subtle) changes
with respect to 8...Qe8. True, the queen is not ready to defend the knight on
h5, but keeping it on the h4-d8 diagonal offers him some tactical ideas,
allowing him to simply sacrifice the knight in certain lines.} 9. Nh2 $1 {
A well-timed deviation from all known plans. White simply prevents ...f7-f5
and will soon drive the black knight back from h5. The knight only apparently
stands badly on h2. After g3-g4 White can either maneuver it to g3 or, after
g4-g5, jump directly to g4. These are helped by the fact that ...Nh5-f6 will
count as a waste of time, while if deprived of early tactics Black may find ...
Qe7 not very useful in the long run, either.} ({There are some concrete
problems with the familiar} 9. Be3 {For instance} f5 (9... Nd7 10. Nd2 {
[%cal Gf1e2] followed by Be2 may gain a tempo over the normal lines.}) 10. exf5
gxf5 11. Ng5 ({The alternative is} 11. Nh4 Nf6 {when due to the threat ...
f5-f4 White has to move with a developed piece again:} 12. Bg5) 11... Nf6 {
Due to the threat ...f5-f4 White has to deviate from the harmonious course of
development with} 12. Qe2) ({With the queen on e7 instead of e8,} 9. Be2 Na6
10. Be3 {runs into} f5 11. exf5 gxf5 12. Ng5 f4 $1 {The g5 knight is hanging
and taking on h5 does not attack the queen.}) 9... Na6 ({It is too early for} 
9... f5 10. exf5 Rxf5 11. g4 Rxf2 12. Kxf2 Qh4+ 13. Kg1 Qg3+ 14. Bg2 $18 {
and Black does not have a perpetual.}) ({In order to prove the coherence of
Nf3-h2, we should check what happens if Black switches to the familiar
patterns with} 9... Qe8 10. Be2 Nf6 11. g4 Na6 12. Nf1 Nc5 13. Ng3 a5 14. h4
$16 {[%csl Gg3] The knight surely stands better on g3 than on d2, and these
tempi just came for free!}) 10. Be3 (10. Be2 {slightly weakens the kingside
and allows Black to display one of his hidden ideas.} f5 $1 11. exf5 Rxf5 12.
Ng4 (12. g4 Rxf2 13. Kxf2 Qh4+ 14. Kf1 Qxh3+ $11 {White has to accept a draw
by perpetual} 15. Ke1 $2 Ng3 $19) 12... Rf8 13. h4 Nf4 $3 14. Bf1 (14. gxf4
exf4 15. Kf1 h5 16. Nh2 Qxh4 {with overwhelming compensation for the piece.
Once again we see that the queen is well placed on the dark diagonal.}) 14...
Nc5 $17 {Khairullin,I (2652)-Grischuk,A (2774) Berlin 2015 (1/2, 27)}) 10...
Nc5 {After White has defended f2, the similar line as above does not work
anymore.} 11. h4 {A completely different way of advancing the kingside pawns
than what we have been used to so far. But in the end, the structure will
become familiar.} (11. b4 {once again allows Black to display the dynamic
potential of his position:} Nd7 12. Be2 a5 13. a3 {Del Rio de Angelis,S (2512)
-Vallejo Pons,F (2684) Bilbao 2015 (1-0, 36)} Nf4 $1 14. gxf4 (14. Bf1 f5 $17)
14... exf4 15. Bd4 (15. Bd2 Nf6 $15 16. f3 $2 axb4 17. axb4 Nxe4 18. fxe4 Qh4+)
15... Bxd4 16. Qxd4 axb4 17. Nb1 Nc5 18. Nd2 Rxa3 $17 {with strong initiative
for the piece in all cases.}) 11... a5 12. Be2 Nf6 13. Qc2 {White has gained a
tempo, but his knight is on h2 instead of d2. If he manages to carry out g4-g5,
this would become a plus, as the knight could jump to g4.} c6 ({Making things
easy for White, but fighting against the h2-knight with} 13... h5 {looks risky:
} 14. Bg5 Qe8 (14... c6 {would allow} 15. g4) 15. O-O-O {[%cal Gf2f3,Gg3g4]
followed by f2-f3 and g3-g4, when White's attacking chances look more
realistic than Black's.}) 14. g4 Na6 15. g5 Ne8 16. h5 Nb4 17. Qd2 cxd5 18.
cxd5 Bd7 19. O-O-O $16 {With a clear advantage for White in Tomashevsky, E 
(2749)-Grischuk, A (2780) Khanty-Mansiysk 2015 (½-½, 74).} *

