{[%evp 0,15,42,31,16,-16,56,55,31,31,31,37,37,21,65,33,81,53]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 c5 {This is the other main way of
attacking White's center. But in the resulting structures h2-h3 proves useful,
too.} 7. d5 {The most principled answer.} (7. dxc5 {is usually answered with}
Qa5) 7... Na6 {Black prepares the queenside break ...b7-b5 delaying the
decision about where to advance the e-pawn. But this is a rather slow plan.} ({
The structure resulting after} 7... e5 {looks solid for Black, but since he
does not have the c5-square for his knights Black will soon experience
problems with coordination.} 8. Bg5 {This pin is effective due to Black's
problems with space.} h6 {Trying to get some breathing space but weakening the
kingside.} ({The alternatives are not rosier either.} 8... a6 9. a4 Nbd7 10. g4
h6 11. Be3 h5 12. Ng5 $16 {[%csl Rh5] Black cannot really afford to open the
h-file, thus turning the h5-pawn into a weakness.}) (8... Na6 9. Qd2 Bd7 10. a3
{[%cal Gb2b4] and White can soon start the typical attack with b2-b4.}) 9. Be3
Nh5 {Trying to get some activity with a familiar move.} ({If} 9... Nbd7 10. Qd2
Kh7 11. g4 a6 12. a4 Ng8 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gf7f5] Rajcevic,S (2146)-Adamovic,S 
(1996) Belgrade 2006 (½-½, 23), planning ...Ne7 and ...f5,} 13. g5 $5 h5 14.
h4 {[%cal Gf1h3] Black is very passive. White can prepare f2-f4 at his own
leisure. In the process he will most likely develop his bishop to h3, while
the f3-knight would go to d3.}) 10. Qd2 Kh7 11. g3 f5 (11... Nd7 12. Bd3) ({or
} 11... Na6 12. Bd3 {leave Black's structure immobile.}) 12. exf5 gxf5 13. Nh4
f4 14. Qd3+ Kg8 15. Bd2 $16) (7... b5 {is examined in line 13.}) ({For the
main continuation} 7... e6 {see line 14.}) 8. Bd3 Nc7 9. Bg5 h6 10. Be3 a6 11.
Qd2 Kh7 12. a4 Rb8 13. a5 {Immediately after playing this I understood that I
could have simply ignored the threat ...b7-b5:} (13. O-O b5 14. axb5 axb5 15.
cxb5 Bd7 16. Ra5 $16 {as} Ncxd5 $2 17. Nxd5 {defends the rook.}) 13... b5 ({
Black has to react at once as} 13... e5 14. b4 cxb4 15. Na4 $16) 14. axb6 Rxb6
15. Ra2 ({Missing a favorable moment to open the center:} 15. e5 $1 dxe5 (15...
Nfe8 16. e6 $16) 16. Bxc5 Rb8 17. Nxe5 $16) 15... e5 16. O-O ({In the game I
unnecessarily started kingside play, weakening the defense of the opposite
wing:} 16. g4 Bd7 17. Ne2 Qb8 18. Ng3 a5 {with certain black counterplay in
Marin,M (2525)-Ehlvest,J (2590) Calcutta 1999 (0-1, 25).}) 16... Bd7 ({Black
gets nowhere with his kingside attack after} 16... Nh5 17. Rb1 f5 18. Qd1 f4
19. Bd2 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc3a4,Gb2b4] followed by Na4 and b2-b4 soon.}) 17. Rb1
Qb8 18. Na4 {This creates some threats around c5 already.} Bxa4 {An obvious
concession, but there was nothing better:} (18... Rb4 19. Nxc5 dxc5 20. Bxc5
Rb3 21. Bxf8 Qxf8 22. Bc2 Rb8 23. Nxe5 Nxe4 24. Nxg6 $18) (18... Rb3 19. Bxc5
dxc5 20. Nxc5 $16) 19. Rxa4 $14 {White has more space, the better structure,
and two bishops. True, Black's position is solid but the play is one-sided.} *

