{[%evp 0,14,19,14,32,-14,54,43,25,37,44,45,46,47,46,47,98]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6
3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 c5 7. d5 b5 $5 {A continuation in the
spirit of the Volga/Benko gambit. But since White has not made important
commitments (such as developing his queen's bishop far from the queenside)
Black will mainly struggle for a draw, without clear chances to reach it.} 8.
cxb5 a6 9. a4 $1 {The strongest.} ({Playing in a similar way as in the Volga
Gambit offers Black reasonable compensation, for instance} 9. bxa6 Qa5 10. Bd2
Bxa6) ({or} 9. b6 Nbd7 10. Be2 Nxb6) 9... e6 {Black has nothing better than
opening the center before White completes his kingside development.
Unfortunately, this weakens his structure a bit.} (9... axb5 {just helps White
to develop:} 10. Bxb5 Ba6 (10... Na6 {is the start of a slow maneuver, placing
the knight on a square of purely aesthetical value.} 11. O-O Nb4 12. Be3 Ba6
13. Qd2 Qa5 14. e5 Ne8 15. Bh6 $16 {Notkin,M (2505)-Ivanovic,B (2515) Vrnjacka
Banja 1998 (1-0, 73)}) 11. Be3 Bxb5 12. axb5 {The b5 pawn is actually strong,
as it prevents Black from setting up the usual pressure along the b-file.} Nbd7
13. O-O Qc7 14. Qe2 Rfb8 15. Nd2 Nb6 16. Ra6 Qb7 17. Nb3 e6 18. Na5 Qd7 19. Nc6
$18 {Eljanov,P (2487)-Weetik,V (2365) St Petersburg 2000 (1-0, 39)}) 10. dxe6
Bxe6 ({Black does not manage to put his centre into motion after} 10... fxe6
11. e5 $1 Ne8 12. Be3 {Putting c5 under observation.} Bb7 13. Be2 axb5 14. Nxb5
Qa5+ 15. Bd2 Qd8 16. Nxd6 (16. O-O dxe5 17. Be3 $16) 16... Nxd6 17. exd6 Bxf3
$2 {An unnecessary concession in a bad position.} (17... Bd5 18. Bc3 Nc6 19.
Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Rc1 $16) (17... Bxb2 $2 18. Rb1 $18) 18. Bxf3 Ra6 19. Bc3 Rxd6
20. Qe2 $18 {Rajlich,I (2432)-Piorun,K (2274) Warsaw 2006 (1-0, 44)}) 11. Be2
axb5 {Taking on b5 looks more reasonable now than on the previous move, as
White has already moved with his bishop.} ({But in principle leads to similar
play and sometimes to transpositions.} 11... d5 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14.
O-O (14. Qxd5 Bxd5 15. Ra3 $16) 14... Qxd1 (14... axb5 {could transpose below.}
) 15. Rxd1 Bb3 {1-0 (48) Grivas,E (2425)-Dedes,N (2275) Athens 1991} 16. Rd6
$18) 12. Bxb5 d5 ({Another possible plan is} 12... Na6 {[%cal Gd6d5] planning .
.d6-d5 under hopefully improved circumstances.} 13. O-O Nc7 14. Be2 {Actually
not a necessary retreat.} (14. Be3 $5 Nxb5 15. axb5 Bc4 16. Re1 $16 Rb8 $2 17.
Ra6 $18) 14... Qe7 (14... d5 {would have been somewhat better, using the fact
that the knights are ready to get coordinated.} 15. exd5 Nfxd5 16. Ne4 Qe7 17.
Bg5 f6 18. Bd2 Bxh3 19. Qc2 Bf5 20. Bd3 Nb4 21. Bxb4 cxb4 22. Nd4 $14 {Black's
weaknesses on the light squares leave him struggling despite having retrieved
the pawn.}) 15. Re1 Rfd8 16. Bf1 h6 17. Bd2 Qd7 18. Qc1 Kh7 19. Nb5 Nce8 20.
Bc3 $16 {Dobosz,H (2404)-Rausis,I (2537) Gerlingen 2007 (1-0, 60)}) 13. exd5
Nxd5 14. Nxd5 ({I find this simpler and better than} 14. Bd2 Nb4 ({Black
should cary out the familiar regrouping with} 14... Na6 15. O-O Nac7 $14 {
with some compensation for the pawn.}) 15. O-O N8c6 16. Bg5 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 Nd4
{Anastasian,A (2559)-Nalbandian,T (2471) Yerevan 2009 (1-0, 44)} 18. Nxd4 cxd4
19. Ne4 Bb3 20. Be7 Bxd1 21. Rxd1 $16) 14... Bxd5 (14... Qxd5 15. O-O Na6 (
15... Nc6 16. Qe2 Nd4 17. Nxd4 cxd4 18. Rd1 $16) {Alvarez,J (2390) -Gomez
Fontal,F (2335) Cuba 1997 (0-1, 66)} 16. a5 $5 $16) 15. O-O Nc6 16. Be3 (16.
Ra3 {played in Bui,V (2458)-Mok,T (2363) Yangon 2011 (1-0, 56) would offer
Black chances after} c4 $5 {spoiling White's coordination a bit.}) 16... Bxf3 {
Black in vain hopes to get some relief by transposing to a position with
opposite-colored bishops.} ({But other moves are no better.} 16... Bxb2 17. Rb1
Bd4 {Otherwise Bxc5.} 18. Nxd4 cxd4 19. Bh6 Re8 20. Qd2 $16) (16... c4 17. Qe2
Rc8 18. Rac1 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 Nd4 20. Bxd4 Qxd4 21. Rfd1 Qxb2 22. Rxc4 $16 {
with the same evaluation as in the game continuation.}) 17. Qxf3 Nd4 18. Bxd4
Bxd4 19. Rad1 Qa5 20. b3 $16 {The a-pawn is not dangerous just by itself. But
Black will have to dedicate part of his attention to prevent it from advancing
to a6, leaving White free hands for a kingside attack.} Rad8 21. Rfe1 Rd6 22.
Re4 Rf6 23. Rf4 Rxf4 24. Qxf4 Rc8 25. Bc4 Rc7 26. Qd2 Qa7 27. a5 Rd7 28. Kh1
Rd6 29. a6 $18 {Cvetkovic,S (2407)-Fugulyan,G (1978) Budva 2009 (1-0, 34)} *

