{[%evp 0,24,25,30,30,-16,37,37,37,37,43,37,37,25,50,50,87,62,96,57,55,20,27,39,
39,39,27]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 c5 7. d5 e6
{The most principled move, trying to reduce White's domination in the centre
and turning the game typical for either the Benoni or the Hromadka Indian.} ({
Many times, Black inserts} 7... a6 8. a4 (8. Bd3 {allows Black reasonable
Volga/Benko like counterplay after} b5 9. cxb5 axb5 10. Nxb5 Na6 11. Nc3 Nb4
12. Bc4 Qb6 13. O-O Ba6) {before breaking with} 8... e6 {This is aimed at
preventing a later Nb5 should the queen embark active kingside operations.} 9.
Bd3 exd5 10. exd5 ({Since the freeing ...b7-b5 is not available anymore, White
can seriously consider transposing to a genuine Benoni with} 10. cxd5 {From my
own experience I know that in this setup it is not easy for Black to get
counterplay.}) 10... Re8+ 11. Be3 Nbd7 {In principle there are no big
differences with respect to the main line:} (11... Rxe3+ {is an optically
interesting exchange sacrifice, but it offers Black only practical drawing
chances, due to his control of the dark squares.} 12. fxe3 Qe7 {In Kaidanov, G
(2415)-Glek, I (2405) Lvov 1985 (1/2, 22) White should have played as in the
similar position without the moves ...a7-a6 and a2-a4:} 13. Qd2 Nbd7 14. O-O
$14) 12. O-O Nh5 (12... Ne5 {Without the intermediate ...Nh5 this allows White
to gain time for his development.} 13. Nxe5 Rxe5 14. Bf4 Re8 15. Qd2 Nh5 16.
Bh2 f5 17. a5 Be5 18. Bxe5 Rxe5 19. f4 Re8 20. Na4 Bd7 21. Nb6 Rb8 22. Kh2 Nf6
23. Bc2 ({It is probably best to keep the main strategic threat b2-b4 in
reserve, but} 23. b4 {is also quite strong:} cxb4 24. Rac1 Qc7 25. c5 Ne4 26.
Bxe4 Rxe4 27. c6 $16 {Huzman,A (2490)-Herman,S Eger 1988 (1-0, 37)}) 23... Qc7
24. Qc3 Ne4 25. Bxe4 Rxe4 26. Rae1 Rbe8 27. Rxe4 Rxe4 28. Re1 Rxe1 29. Qxe1 $16
) 13. Qd2 Ne5 ({If} 13... f5 14. Bg5 {, making use of the fact that Nb5 is not
available with} Qc7 {as in Ivanov, S (2550)-Kuzuev, D (2350) St Petersburg
1998 (½-½, 44) allows} 15. g4 $1 fxg4 16. hxg4 Nhf6 17. Rae1 $16) 14. Be2 ({
I have obtained excellent results with black after} 14. Nxe5 Rxe5 {when
Black's pieces are suddenly very active.}) 14... Bd7 15. Rfe1 Qb6 16. Nxe5 Rxe5
{I had analyzed this line for Black several decades ago, but for some reasons
I did not consider} 17. Bxh5 $1 Rxh5 18. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rh5] Sargissian,G 
(2643)-Marin, M (2556) Plovdiv 2008 (1-0, 32) The black rook has no simple way
back into the game.}) 8. Bd3 exd5 (8... Na6 9. O-O Nc7 {The start of a plan
intended to keep Black's flexibility. Black hopes to provoke a2-a4 in order to
return with the knight to b4 and block the center with ...e6-e5. But if White
finds a way to keep his central stability and avoid a2-a4 the knight will be
passive on c7.} 10. Bg5 (10. a4 Na6) 10... h6 11. Be3 exd5 (11... e5 12. Qd2
Kh7 13. Ne1 Rb8 14. a3 Nh5 15. Be2 Nf4 16. Bxf4 exf4 17. Qxf4 f5 18. exf5 Bxf5
19. Qd2 a6 20. a4 h5 21. Bd3 $16 {Shulman,Y (2616)-Leitao,R (2601)
Khanty-Mansiysk 2007 (1-0, 43)}) 12. exd5 b5 13. b3 Re8 14. Qd2 Kh7 ({
Unfortunately} 14... b4 15. Ne2 Ne4 {does not work out well:} 16. Bxe4 Bxa1 17.
Rxa1 Rxe4 18. Bxh6 $16 {[%csl Rc7,Rg8] offers White too much compensation for
the exchange as the black king is weak and the c7-knight still passive.}) 15.
Rae1 {White has now completed his development without making any concession.}
b4 16. Ne2 Ne4 17. Qc2 f5 18. g4 {with all his pieces in the right place,
White starts the decisive attack.} Qf6 19. Ng3 fxg4 20. Nh2 Ng5 21. hxg4 Qf7
22. f4 Rxe3 23. Rxe3 Bd4 24. fxg5 Bxe3+ 25. Kg2 Bf4 26. Ne4 {1-0 Yakovich,Y 
(2534)-Marin, M (2604) Gothenburg 2001.}) 9. exd5 (9. cxd5 {allows} b5 {
as analyzed in my Benoni repertoire article.}) 9... Re8+ 10. Be3 Bh6 {A
tempting move, yielding Black the control over e5 but delaying his development
and opening the f-file for White's attack.} (10... b5 {is not entirely sound:}
11. Nxb5 Ne4 12. O-O a6 ({A beautiful classical game went} 12... Bxb2 13. Bxe4
Rxe4 14. Qc2 Rxe3 15. Qxb2 Rxf3 {Black hoped for 16.gxf3 Bxh3 retrieving the
exchange due to the threat ...Qg5 but the next move puts things in their place:
} 16. Rfe1 $3 {[%cal Gb5d6,Gb5c7,Gg2f3] Suddenly it appears that Black is
completely undeveloped. White has threats such as Nxd6, Nc7 and gxf3.} Bd7 17.
gxf3 Qg5+ 18. Kh1 Na6 19. Nxd6 Bxh3 {In Ivkov,B (2525)-Gheorghiu,F (2540)
Buenos Aires 1979 (1-0, 32) the fastest win was} 20. Qh8+ $1 Kxh8 21. Nxf7+)
13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nd7 (14... Bxc3 {wastes even more time.} 15. Rc1 Bg7 16.
Bg5 f6 17. Bf4 Bf8 18. Qc2 Ra7 19. Rfe1 Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Re7 21. Rb1 $16) 15. Qd2
Ne5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Rac1 f5 {In principle Black has hopes to hold this
position as for the time being White's extra pawn is not too relevant. But
play remains one-sided.} 18. Rfe1 Bd7 19. Bg5 Qc7 20. h4 h5 21. g3 Bg7 22. Bf4
Rxe1+ 23. Rxe1 Re8 24. Rb1 Rb8 25. Rb3 $16 {Marin,M (2580)-Moldovan,D (2438)
Mamaia 2015 (1-0, 33)}) (10... Nbd7 {may lead to similar play as after 7...a6:}
11. O-O Nh5 12. Qd2 Ne5 (12... f5 13. Bg5 Ndf6 14. Rae1 Bd7 {Nogueiras
Santiago, J (2560)-Barlov, D (2520) Saint John 1988 (½-½, 17). Now was a
good moment to start combining play on both wings with} 15. a3 $14) 13. Be2 $1
Nxf3+ (13... Bd7 14. Rae1 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Qh4 16. Bg5 Qxc4 17. Ne4 $16) 14. Bxf3
{In the lines below Black's delay in development is obvious.} Nf6 (14... Ng3
15. Rfe1 Nf5 16. Bg5 f6 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. Re1 Qf8 19. Bf4 Nd4 20. Bd1 f5 21.
Ba4 $16) 15. Bg5 Bd7 16. Qf4 Re5 {Aleksandrov,A (2601)-Andreikin,D (2509)
Moscow 2007 (½-½, 40)} 17. Rae1 $16) ({I have once sinned with the
strategically risky} 10... Bf5 {, too:} 11. Bxf5 gxf5 12. O-O Ne4 13. Ne2 Nd7
14. Rb1 Kh8 15. Qc1 $1 {Played with a subtle idea.} Qf6 16. Ng3 Rg8 17. Bg5 $1
{Quite a shock! Black cannot defend his weaknesses anymore.} Nxg3 (17... Nxg5
18. Qxg5 $18) {Gheorghiu,F (2540)-Marin,M (2445) Warsaw 1987 (½-½, 22)} 18.
fxg3 Qg6 19. Bf4 $18) ({The same as with ...a7-a6 and a2-a4 inserted, this
only offers practical drawing chances.} 10... Rxe3+ 11. fxe3 Qe7 12. O-O Nbd7
13. Qd2 Ne5 ({Or if} 13... Nh5 14. Rf2 {[%cal Gg2g4] planning g2-g4.}) 14. Nxe5
Qxe5 15. Rf3 {White's advance in development is obvious now.} Bd7 (15... Nd7
16. Raf1 f5 17. e4 $16) 16. Raf1 Rf8 17. Qf2 Qe7 18. Rxf6 $1 Bxf6 19. Qxf6
Qxe3+ 20. Rf2 Qxd3 21. Qxd6 Bf5 22. Qxc5 $18 {Gelfand,B (2755)-Morozevich,A 
(2760) Moscow 2013 (1-0, 33)}) (10... Nh5 {tries to speed up the kingside plan,
but without developing his queenside Black can hardly achieve much.} 11. O-O f5
12. Bg5 Bf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Re1 Rxe1+ 15. Qxe1 Bd7 16. Qd2 Na6 17. a3 Re8 18.
Rb1 {Black's position remains very unpleasant due to White's central space
advantage and Black's kingside weaknesses..} Re7 19. g3 Be8 20. Kg2 Ng7 21. Ne2
b6 22. Qh6 Bd7 23. Nf4 Ne8 {Beliavsky,A (2655)-Damljanovic,B (2585) Belgrade
1991 (1-0, 54)} 24. Ng5 $5 Qg7 25. Qxg7+ Nxg7 26. h4 $16) (10... Na6 {is a
slightly different version of ...Na6 examined above. With the central
structure already defined, White can parry the threat ...b7-b5 with a2-a4.} 11.
O-O Nc7 12. a4 Na6 ({The queenside plan is too slow to continue:} 12... a6 13.
a5 Rb8 14. Qd2 b5 15. axb6 Rxb6 16. Bg5 Qe7 17. Na4 Rb4 18. Qc2 Bd7 19. Bd2
Bxa4 20. Rxa4 Rb7 21. Re1 $16 {Damljanovic,B (2583)-Paunovic,D (2512) Zaragoza
2004 (1-0, 46)}) 13. Rc1 $1 {White prepares to keep the bishop on the
attacking diagonal without obstructing the major pieces' communication.} Nb4
14. Bb1 {The knight is a bit out of play actually. With pawns on e4 and e5
Black would be safer, of course, but here play is one-sided.} a6 15. Qd2 Bd7
16. Bh6 b5 17. b3 bxc4 18. bxc4 Nh5 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Ne4 Bf5 21. Ng3 Bxb1 22.
Rxb1 Nxg3 23. fxg3 Ra7 (23... h6 24. g4 Qd7 25. g5 h5 26. Qf4 $14) {Ovetchkin,
R (2548)-Isupov,V (2421) Sochi 2006 (1-0, 26)} 24. Rxb4 $1 $18) 11. O-O Bxe3
12. fxe3 Qe7 (12... Rxe3 {Taking the pawn offers White huge advances in
development and initiative.} 13. Qd2 Qe7 (13... Re7 14. Ng5 Nbd7 15. Qf4 Re5
16. Nge4 $16) 14. Nd1 {[%csl Re3] Just winning the exchange.} Rxf3 15. Rxf3
Nbd7 16. Nf2 Ne5 17. Re3 Nfd7 {Optically this may seem playable for Black, as
he has perfect control over e5. But his queenside is undeveloped and White can
start preparing an exchange sacrifice on e5.} 18. Rae1 f5 19. Qc3 a6 20. Bf1
$16 {[%cal Gf2d3] followed by Nd3.}) 13. e4 Nbd7 14. Qd2 Kg7 ({Another fine
attacking game for White went} 14... Rf8 15. Bc2 Nh5 16. Qh6 f6 17. g4 Ng7 18.
e5 $3 {A thematic break, just when Black hoped to block with ...Ne5.} Nxe5 (
18... fxe5 19. Ng5 Ne8 20. Bxg6 $18) (18... dxe5 19. d6 Qxd6 20. Rad1 Qe6 21.
Be4 $18) 19. Nxe5 Qxe5 (19... dxe5 20. Rad1 Ne8 21. d6 Nxd6 22. Bxg6 hxg6 23.
Qxg6+ Kh8 24. Qh6+ Kg8 25. Nd5 $16) 20. Rae1 Qd4+ 21. Kg2 $18 {Ding,L (2628)
-Vocaturo,D (2570) Moscow 2011 (1-0, 36)}) 15. Rf2 Rf8 16. Raf1 Ne8 17. Bc2 {
Time has come to activate the bishop, aiming at exchanging one of the knights
at the right moment, thus reducing Black's chances for a blockade.} Ne5 18.
Nxe5 dxe5 (18... Qxe5 19. Ba4 Nc7 20. Rf6 $14) 19. Ba4 Nd6 (19... Bd7 20. Bxd7
Qxd7 21. g4 $16) 20. Rf6 $1 h6 (20... Qxf6 21. Rxf6 Kxf6 22. Qf2+ Kg7 23. Qxc5
$18) 21. Qf2 $16 Nf5 $2 22. Rxf5 gxf5 23. exf5 f6 24. Ne4 $18 {Shirov,A (2700)
-Kovacevic,A (2525) Belgrade 1997 (1-0, 32)} *

