{[%evp 0,15,61,42,31,-29,56,41,57,57,55,42,35,31,68,68,93,93]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 c6 {The only alternative to the main
lines with independent value.} (6... Na6 {is best answered with} 7. Be3 {
keeping the game along our main repertoire should Black play ...e7-e5.} e5 ({
True, Black can deviate with} 7... c5 8. d5 Nc7 {when we do not have Bg5
anymore. But the play does not change that much. The best chance for
counterplay seems to be} 9. Bd3 e6 10. O-O exd5 11. exd5 b5 {but the calm} 12.
b3 $14 {[%csl Rc7] maintains the space advantage and leaves the knight passive
on c7, with chances to start a massive piece and pawns attack on the kingside.}
) 8. d5 {This position could also occur via the 6...e5 7.d5 Na6 move order,
not investigated in the respective sections. The point is that Black cannot
avoid a transposition to known lines:} Nc5 (8... Nh5 9. g3) 9. Nd2) ({The same
applies to} 6... Nbd7 7. Be3 e5 8. d5 Nh5 (8... Nc5 9. Nd2) 9. g3 {when the
d7-knight should soon jump to c5 anyway.}) 7. Be3 a6 {The logical follow up of
the previous move. Black refrains from playing in the center and prepares some
queenside counterplay. Play will take independent character now.} 8. Be2 b5 ({
If} 8... Nbd7 9. Qc2 e5 {White should already refrain from blocking the center,
as his queen would be exposed on c2. Instead, he could use the weakness on b6
created by ...c7-c6 and a7-a6 with} 10. dxe5 (10. d5 cxd5 11. cxd5 b5 12. g4
Nb6 13. Nd2 Bd7 {[%cal Ga8c8] followed by ...Rc8 leaves White behind in the
mutual plan race.}) 10... Nxe5 ({If} 10... dxe5 11. c5 {Black has even bigger
space problems.}) 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Rd1 Qc7 13. O-O Be6 14. Na4 Nd7 15. c5 $14
{[%cal Gd1d2,Gf1d1,Ge2c4] White will double rooks on the d-file followed by
Bc4.}) 9. e5 $1 {Since Black has neglected the center, this now becomes
White's territory.} Ne8 (9... Nfd7 10. exd6 exd6 11. O-O bxc4 (11... b4 12. Na4
a5 13. c5 $16) 12. Bxc4 Nb6 13. Bg5 $1 ({It is better to hurry with this move.
If} 13. Bb3 N8d7 14. Bg5 Nf6 {as in Heimann,A (2560)-Hug,W (2473) Switzerland
2016 (½-½, 57) White could retain just some small plus with} 15. Rc1 $14)
13... Qc7 14. Bb3 N8d7 15. Qd2 Bb7 16. Qf4 $16) 10. O-O (10. Qd2 {is also
playable:} Nd7 11. Bh6 Nb6 {Kreisl,R (2400)-Manolache,M (2561) Plovdiv 2012 
(0-1, 47)} 12. b3 dxe5 13. Bxg7 Nxg7 14. Nxe5 Qc7 15. Rc1 $14) 10... Nd7 {
The most flexible continuation.} ({If} 10... dxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rfxd1 Nc7
13. Rd2 bxc4 ({The blocking} 13... Ne6 {leaves Black without obvious
possibilities of developing the queenside after} 14. Rad1 $16) (13... Nd7 {
leads to the opening of the position, favouring White who is better developed:}
14. Rad1 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Bf3 $1 {Black's queenside is vulnerable now.}
bxc4 17. Bxc6 Rb8 18. Ba7 Rxb2 (18... Rb4 19. Bc5 $16) 19. Rxb2 Bxc3 20. Rc2
Bf6 21. Rxc4 $16) 14. Bxc4 Nd7 15. e6 $5 {Not the only move, but quite a good
one.} Nxe6 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Rad1 Nf6 18. Bd4 $14 {With perfect control on the
dark squares despite Black's extra pawn.}) {Ilivitzki,G-Nezhmetdinov,R Rostov
on Don (Russia) 1954 (0-1, 29)} 11. Re1 dxe5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 (12... Bb7 13. f4
$14) 13. dxe5 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Bxe5 15. Bf3 $14 {with a familiar picture.} *

