{[#]Encouraged by the white king's delay in the centre Black has started an
early attack with his queenside completely underdeveloped. Can White refute
this optimistic action?} 15. Qe2 $1 {The central pawns are so vulnerable
without the help of the queenside pieces that White can afford preparing to
take on e4 under the best circumstances.} (15. Ngxe4 $6 {was the game move
which offered Black adequate compensation after} Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Nd7 17. O-O Ne5
$11 {Navara,D (2715)-Kovalev,A (2470) Pardubice 2013 (1-0, 36)}) (15. Bxf4 $2 {
exposes White to} Nh5 $15) 15... a4 (15... f3 16. Bxf3 $18) (15... e3 16. fxe3
Nxg4 17. exf4 Qxe2+ 18. Nxe2 $18 {[%cal Gh1g1,Gg5e6] followed by Rg1, Ne6 with
a decisive advantage in development and initiative.}) (15... Na6 {is similar
to the main line:} 16. Ngxe4 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Qh4 18. O-O-O $16) 16. Ngxe4 Nxe4
17. Bxe4 $1 {[%cal Ge4h7] This is the difference: in the game, this way of
recapturing would lose the bishop to ...Bxc3+. Black has to spend a tempo to
parry Bxh7+ winning the queen.} Be5 18. O-O-O $16 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gf2f3,Gh3h4]
White has stabilized after winning the pawn and can prepare his attack with
f2-f3, h3-h4 and so on, while his king is safe enough.} *

