{[#]White has strong initiative but he needs to continue accurately as if
allowed to play ...Rh8 and ...a5-a4 Black would be doing fine. There are two
moves leading to a large advantage but in all the tests inspired by this game,
I have chosen a slightly subjective approach, making a clear distinction
between the continuations leading to a mating attack or just to an
overwhelming positional advantage. White to move and complete the game by a
decisive attack.} 22. Qg4 $3 {This apparently peaceful move clears the h-file
for the rook, maintaining the threat Nb3, undermining Black's control over e6
and d7, in reserve.} (22. Nb3 $1 {This move, played in Matlakov, M (2665)
-Gladyszev, O (2446) St Petersburg 2012 (1-0, 25) is objectively very strong,
too, but as you will have the occasion to prove in the next test, White is not
mating soon.}) 22... a4 {Preventing Nb3.} (22... Qb6 23. Nb3 Rcd8 24. Nxc5 Qxc5
25. Rh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6g6] Threatening 26.Rxg6 and if 26...Kxg6 then 27.Qf5+
mating soon.} Bxh6 26. gxh6 Qxf2 27. Rg1 Rg8 28. h7 $18) (22... Rh8 23. Nb3 $18
{[%cal Gg4e6,Gg4d7] followed by Qd7+ or Qe6+.}) 23. Rh6 {[%cal Gh6g6]
Threatening the familiar Rxg6.} Rf8 {Defending the f5-square in advance, thus
parrying Rxg6.} (23... Bxh6 24. gxh6 $18 {[%cal Gd1g1,Yd2f3] followed by Rg1
and sometimes Nf3.}) 24. Nf3 $18 {[%cal Gf3h4] Black has no adequate defence
against Nh4.} *

