{[#]The earlier phase of this game was quoted in the theoretical article. A
few moves earlier White has refrained from gxf6 (en passant) which would have
been the simplest way to spare him problems regarding his knight on h2 and
bishop on e3. But his continuation was by no means worse, only that now he has
to take a crucial decision about how to meet the threat ...f5-f4.} 22. a3 $1 {
[%cal Gf5f4] This is the safest way to an advantage. If the knight retreats
White gets a queenside domination, with the contribution of the e3-bishop.} (
22. f3 $6 {This ultra solid move was played in the game, but it leads to
unclear play, as it restricts the h2-knight even more.} Nc7 23. Rc1 Nba6 24.
Bd3 b4 25. Ne2 Nb5 26. Rc6 $5 Rfb8 27. Rhc1 {Tomashevsky,E (2749)-Grischuk,A 
(2780) Khanty-Mansiysk 2015 (½-½, 74) In the next test you are kindly
invited to play with black.}) (22. Nxb5 $6 {is premature due to} f4 23. Bb6
Bxb5 24. Bxb5 Qb7) (22. Nf3 $5 {is an interesting and strong move, which is
not easy to decide upon over the board, though, as it sacrifices a piece out
of blue.} f4 23. Nh4 $1 fxe3 24. Qxe3 {[%cal Gh4g6] Black cannot prevent Nxg6.
yielding White two pawns for the piece and a promising attack, as Black is
poorly coordinated.} Rf4 (24... Qf7 25. Nxg6 $1 Qxg6 26. Bh5 {forces Black to
return the piece with} Nxd5 {, without chances to save the game after} 27. Nxd5
) 25. Nxg6 Qxg5 26. Rdg1 Qf6 27. Rh8+ $1 Kf7 (27... Bxh8 28. Nxf4+ Bg7 29. Nh5
$16) 28. Rh2 Kg8 29. Bh5 $16) 22... Na6 (22... Nc7 {Unfortunately, this
principled move fails to offer enough compensation for the piece.} 23. axb4
axb4 24. Na2 Na6 25. f3 $1 $16 (25. Nxb4 Nxb4 26. Qxb4 Ra4 27. Qb3 Rxe4 {
offers Black some counterplay based on opening the bishops' diagonals by
advancing his central pawns.})) (22... f4 23. Bb6 Ra6 (23... Na6 24. Nxb5 {
transposes below.}) 24. Bxa5 Rxa5 25. Na2 $16) 23. Nxb5 $1 f4 24. Bb6 Bxb5 25.
Bxb5 Qb7 26. Bc6 $1 {This is the difference! In the similar line above the
c6-square was defended by the knight.} *

