{[#]White has challenged his opponent on the queenside, using a thematic
exchange sacrifice. But his kingside progress is far from easy. How would you
proceed with black?} 27... a4 $3 {[%cal Ga4a3,Ga6c5,Gc5b3] Two exclamation
marks for this natural move may seem exaggerated, but its entire usefulness is
not obvious. Apart from inviting White to display his cards and preparing ...
a4-a3, Black also creates the possibility of ...Nc5 followed by ...Nb3. For
clearer illustration of this idea please refer to the line starting with 27...
Bxc6.} (27... Nc3+ $6 {is premature due to} 28. Nxc3 bxc3 29. R6xc3 $16) (27...
Bxc6 $6 {prematurely weakens the light squares and diagonals.} 28. dxc6 d5 (
28... f4 $2 {is just bad.} 29. Bc4+ Kf8 30. Qd5 Ke8 31. Qg8+ Qf8 32. Qe6+ Qe7
33. Qxg6+ Kd8 34. Bf2 $18) 29. exf5 (29. exd5 Qd6 {allows Black to consolidate}
) 29... gxf5 30. Ng3 Nc3+ ({This exposes the knight but refraining from the
check is also hopeless:} 30... f4 31. Nf5 Qe6 32. Bxf4 exf4 33. Ng4 a4 34.
Ngh6+ Kh8 35. Nxg7 Kxg7 36. Nf5+ Kg8 37. Re1 $18) 31. Ka1 f4 32. Nf5 Qe6 33.
Bxf4 $1 exf4 34. Ng4 $5 $18 {Despite his extra rook, Black cannot defend his
king properly against the massive white attack. By the way, with the pawn on
a4 already, it would be Black to win with} Nc5 {(threatening ...Nb3+) but here
Black is not in time:} 35. Nxg7 Kxg7 36. c7 Rh8 37. bxc3 $18) (27... f4 $6 {
This is the game continuation, with the obvious drawback of concealing the
g4-square to the edged knight.} 28. Bf2 Bf8 (28... Bxc6 29. dxc6 d5 $2 30. exd5
) 29. Ng4 $1 Qxg5 30. Rh1 Qe7 31. Bxb5 Rxb5 {Tomashevsky, E (2749)-Grischuk, A
(2780) Khanty-Mansiysk 2015 (½-½, 74) In the next test you will have the
occasion to finish Black off.}) 28. Bb6 {It is hard to suggest ways for making
progress with white.} (28. Bc4 Kf8 {leads nowhere.}) (28. Nf1 {takes the
knight far from g4 allowing} f4 29. Bf2 Qxg5 {Sadly, the knight cannot return
to g4 as in the game:} 30. Nh2 $2 Qg2 $19) 28... Nc3+ $1 {Based on the fact
that the bishop is hanging now.} 29. Nxc3 (29. bxc3 {also leads to interesting
complications.} bxc3 30. Nxc3 (30. R1xc3 Nb4 $17 {leaves White hanging.}) 30...
Bxc6 31. dxc6 Rxb6+ 32. Ka1 Rxc6 33. Bc4+ $1 {The only way to justify the loss
of the exchange.} Rxc4 34. Qd5+ Qf7 35. Qxa8+ Bf8 36. Qxa6 Qc7 {Due to the
passive knight on h2 Black has full compensation for the piece.} 37. Kb2 Rb4+
38. Kc2 Rc4 39. Kd2 Rd4+ 40. Ke2 {The only way to escape the draw by
repetition.} Be7 {[%cal Ge7g5] followed by ...Bxg5 with a continuing
initiative for the lost piece.}) 29... bxc3 30. Qxc3 (30. R1xc3 {runs into the
familiar} Nb4) 30... Bxc6 31. dxc6 (31. Qxc6 $2 Nb4 $19 {White's bishops are
hanging.}) 31... Rxb6 32. Bxa6 Rbxa6 33. c7 Bf8 34. c8=Q Rxc8 35. Qxc8 Ra7 36.
exf5 Qxg5 $11 {Black has little to fear.} *

