{[#]White's kingside progress is obvious but the threat ... b5-b4 is
unpleasant. How can he maintain the initiative?} 22. Ne6 $1 {A temporary pawn
sacrifice, clearing the g- and d-file, but requiring accurate calculation.}
Nxe6 23. dxe6 b4 $1 {The most principled.} (23... Bxe6 {can be met in more
than one convincing way.} 24. h5 $5 (24. Qxd6 Rc6 $14 {somewhat lowers the
rhythm of attack.}) (24. Rxg7 $5 {may be the simplest, as it simplifies to a
very good ending.} Kxg7 25. Bh6+ Kh8 26. Bxf8 Qxf8 27. Qxd6 $16) 24... Nxh5 25.
Bxh5 Qxh5 26. Qxd6 Rf6 27. Bd4 $5 ({If White wishes to avoid the ensuing
complications, he can choose the quiet} 27. Qxa6 $16 {parrying the threat ...
Bxa2+.}) 27... Qxd1+ $1 {The only way to keep some vague hopes.} (27... Bxa2+
28. Kxa2 Rxd6 29. Bxg7+ Kg8 30. Rxd6 $18 {offers White a decisive material
advantage.}) 28. Rxd1 (28. Nxd1 $2 Bxa2+ 29. Kxa2 Rxd6 30. Bxg7+ Kg8 31. Bh6+
Rg6 {is unclear.}) 28... Bxa2+ 29. Kxa2 Rxd6 30. Bxg7+ Kxg7 31. Rxd6 $16 {
The winning process is not simple, as Black has a potentially dangerous h-pawn,
but the extra knight should eventually prevail.}) (23... Qxe6 24. Qxd6 $14) 24.
e7 $1 {The point of the forced operation.} (24. Nd5 $2 Nxd5 25. Qxd5 {runs into
} Bxe6 {as} 26. Qxd6 $2 Qa4 $1 $19) 24... Qxe7 (24... Rf7 $2 25. Nd5 Nxd5 26.
Qxd5 $18 {Black does not have ...Be6 anymore.}) 25. Na4 {White has stabilized
the position and his king is much safer than Black's. Due to the hanging b and
d pawns Black has problems maintaining his small material advantage.} a5 ({If} 
25... d5 26. Nb6 Rcd8 27. Ka1 $3 {prepares Bd4 with enduring pressure.}) 26.
Qxd6 $14 {Wang,Y (2724)-Bacrot,E (2697) Skopje 2015 (1-0, 54) White is better
regrouped and the black queenside pawns are vulnerable.} *

