{[#]In the previous phase White has sacrificed the h-pawn (g2-g3, ...Nxh3) and
managed to make considerable queenside progress. But with his king in the
centre making progress would not have been easy had Black played the strongest
move now. Can you find it?} 19... e4 $1 {The most principled and strongest
move at the same time. Black activates several pieces, proving that with the
actual coordination White is stuck with his queenside play.} (19... Nf4 $6 {
This thematic move was played in Ivanchuk,V (2719)-Ponomariov,R (2630)
Shenyang 2000 (1-0, 47). In the next test you will have to prove it was
insufficient for an advantage.}) 20. c6 Bc8 21. cxb7 Bxb7 $17 {[%csl Rh2][%cal
Gb7c8,Ga6b8,Gb8d7] If necessary Black can recycle his queenside pieces with ...
Bc8 and .. Nb8-d7, while White cannot do the same with his knight on h2.
Besides, Black keeps his extra pawns and in the long run, he can think of
molesting the white king.} *

